INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(12,'12','11/10/2009','Mireille Mathieu (born July 22, 1946) is a French singer, who besides being very successful in her own country, became a star of international stature, recording in several languages.  	 She was born in Avignon, Vaucluse, France, the oldest daughter of a poor family of fourteen children. She began singing as a small child, appearing in public at the age of four, singing in her church. As a young girl she worked in a factory, where she saved her money to pay for singing lessons.  ','<strong>Mireille Mathieu</strong> (born July 22, 1946) is a French singer, who besides being very successful in her own country, became a star of international stature, recording in several languages.	 	 	 She was born in Avignon, Vaucluse, France, the oldest daughter of a poor family of fourteen children. She began singing as a small child, appearing in public at the age of four, singing in her church. As a young girl she worked in a factory, where she saved her money to pay for singing lessons.	 	 Discovered by Johnny Stark, manager of France%27s biggest star at the time, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Johnny+Hallyday">Johnny Hallyday</a>, she was tutored by orchestra leader <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Paul+Mauriat">Paul Mauriat</a> and song writer André Pascal who wrote &quot;Mon crédo&quot;, &quot;Viens dans ma rue&quot;, &quot;La première étoile&quot; and many other hits for her . After her television performance in 1965 and debut run at the Paris Olympia, she was immediately hailed as the next <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%C3%89dith+Piaf?q=%C3%89dith+Piaf">Édith Piaf</a>, such was her haunting voice.	 	 Singles such as &quot;Mon Credo&quot; and &quot;C%27est Ton Nom&quot; made her a huge star in France and all over Europe while making her a big success in North America and Mexico. Her French cover of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Engelbert+Humperdinck">Engelbert Humperdinck</a>%27s &quot;The Last Waltz&quot; generated much publicity in Great Britain and with hit after hit, she soon toured Canada and the United States where she appeared on the Ed Sullivan Show and the Danny Kaye Show. In Las Vegas, she sang with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Dean+Martin">Dean Martin</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Frank+Sinatra">Frank Sinatra</a> to great applause.	 	 Still much in demand, she continues to perform regularly. She travels frequently, appearing at such venues as New York City%27s Carnegie Hall, Sport Palace in Montreal, Universal Amphitheatre in Los Angeles and Ice Palace of St. Petersburg. She has sold about 150 million copies of her albums in her 40 year career, recorded about 1200 songs in 9 languages, and was the first western singer in history who gave concerts in China. Over the years she sang duets with such luminaries as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Charles+Aznavour">Charles Aznavour</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Barry+Manilow">Barry Manilow</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Paul+Anka">Paul Anka</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Pl%C3%A1cido+Domingo">Plácido Domingo</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Julio+Iglesias">Julio Iglesias</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Tom+Jones">Tom Jones</a> and others.	 	 Songs such as &quot;Acropolis adieu,&quot; &quot;Ne me quitte pas,&quot; and &quot;Santa Maria de la mer,&quot; are considered classics. Her French version of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Roy+Orbison">Roy Orbison</a>%27s ballad, &quot;Blue Bayou&quot;, is regarded by many as one of the best covers of that popular song.	 	 In 1989, President François Mitterrand invited Mireille Mathieu to sing a tribute to General de Gaulle. She gave a series of concerts at the Palais des Congrès in Paris in December 1990. Three years later, she released an album devoted to her all-time idol, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%C3%89dith+Piaf?q=%C3%89dith+Piaf">Édith Piaf</a>.	 	 In January 1996, &quot;Vous lui direz…&quot; was released. Maxime le Forestier wrote one of the titles, &quot;A la moitié de la distance&quot;. She did not choose to perform live in France to promote the album, preferring rather to go to Los Angeles USA, where she triumphed on November 14th with her vibrant tribute to another of her idols, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Judy+Garland">Judy Garland</a>. The performance was a tremendous success she was dressed by Provence couturier, Christian Lacroix and looked stunning for the performance. [1]	 	 In 2002, she released her 37th French albu')

He is only two years old when his family is leaving their village to establish themselves in Tilleur, Wallony, near Liege, a little county in Belgium. He did inherit his fondness of music and singing from his father Peppino. When he is 12 years old he decides to buy his first guitar and joines the band Les Eperviers. His father is approving this decision by helping hom to acced at the Music Accademy. This is a succesful thing to do, because Frederic Francois is winning that same year the singing contest “Festival du Chatelet”, which allows him to make his first record. But he is making his real debut in 1969 when he makes his first 45 tours record whith his actual nickname. He gets married and have a family of his own while he is still young. This thing happens in 1971, the year when his first hits are launched, such like “Je n’ai jamais aime comme je t’aime”, “Laisse-moi vivre ma vie”, “Chicago” and many others. As a tribute to his increasing charismatical success in France, he also conquered by his music Canada, Belgium and the Switzerland. The hits are still going on with titles like ” Mon coeur te dit Je t’aime” in 1984 and ” Je t’aime a l’itallienne” in 1985. Many times till now Frederic Francois is performing many concerts in the Olympia Hall in Paris, such as in the years 1994, 1996, 1998 or 2000. If the name of Frederick Francois is mostly related to the 70’s decade, he still has a great fame and huge success especially among the French music listeners. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(137,'137','20/09/2008','Belgium is a cultural crossroads where Flemish Dutch-speaking and Walloon French-speaking inhabitants mix with German minorities and immigrant communities from Republic of the Congo and other distant countries.  Classical music  During the centuries Belgium produced several notable names in the field of classical music. In the 15th and 16th century composers like Guillaume Dufay, Orlando di Lasso, Josquin des Prez reached European acclaim. André Ernest Modeste Grétry was the most famous composer- born in what is now called Belgium- of the 18th century.','Belgium is a cultural crossroads where Flemish Dutch-speaking and Walloon French-speaking inhabitants mix with German minorities and immigrant communities from Republic of the Congo and other distant countries.	 	 <strong>Classical music</strong>	 	 During the centuries Belgium produced several notable names in the field of classical music. In the 15th and 16th century composers like Guillaume Dufay, Orlando di Lasso, Josquin des Prez reached European acclaim. André Ernest Modeste Grétry was the most famous composer- born in what is now called Belgium- of the 18th century. The 19th century supplied composers like Henri Vieuxtemps, César Franck, Guillaume Lekeu and Eugène Ysaÿe. The famous German composer Ludwig van Beethoven was of Flemish descent and his grandfather (who was born in Mechelen). At the end of the 20th century the most notable Belgian composer was Wim Mertens.	 	 In the field of opera, baritons Jules Bastin and José van Dam have become the most famous and internationally successful Belgian opera singers. In the lighter classical genre Flemish singer Helmut Lotti reached huge international success with his interpretations of popular opera songs for large audiences.	 	 <strong>Blues and Jazz</strong>	 	 One of the most famous jazz instruments, the saxophone, was invented by a Belgian: Adolphe Sax.	 	 Some known Belgian blues artists are Elmore D (who sings in English and Walloon dialect), the Flemish Roland van Campenhout (also known as Roland) and the Brussels band Tomahawk Blues Band.	 	 In the 1930s, the Belgian gypsy guitarist Django Reinhardt became one of the first important jazz musicians to be born in Europe, and one of the most important jazz guitarists of all time. In 1949 Toots Thielemans joined a jam session in Paris with Sidney Bechet, Charlie Parker, Miles Davis, Max Roach and others. He moved to the US in 1952 where he was a member of Charlie Parker%27s All-Stars. Toots Thielemans is often credited by jazz aficionados and jazz critics of being the greatest jazz mouth hamonica player of the century. His music has been used in films like Midnight Cowboy and Turkish Delight, and television series such as Sesame Street and Baantjer. Other wellknown Belgian artists are Aka Moon, Bobby Jaspar, Bert Joris, Philip Catherine, Steve Houben, Octurn and René Thomas	 	 <strong>Folk and other traditional music</strong>	 	 Bobbejaan Schoepen has been a pioneer in Belgian vaudeville and popmusic since the late 1940s. Not only was he the first Belgian singer to manage an international breakthrough, he was also the first to use modern equipment, a personal tourbus and a system of artist sponsoring. He also introduced the first country &amp; western recordings in the Low Countries and Germany. In the 1950s Bobbejaan Schoepen recorded his own absolutely crazy folk music often singing in the dialect of his native Brussels. He is also a virtuoso whistler.	 	 During the 1950s and following decades the most popular, enduring, commercial and critical successful Flemish singer was Will Tura, whose most well known hit in Flanders is &quot;Ik ben zo eenzaam zonder jou&quot; (1963) (&quot;I%27m so lonely without you&quot;).	 	 The most popular and enduring artists in Flanders and the Netherlands who sing in either their Flemish dialect or standard Dutch are Eddy Wally, Raymond van het Groenewoud, De Kreuners, Clouseau, Gorki (band), Noordkaap and de Fixkes.	 	 Walloon folk music has not had as vibrant a revival as Flemish, but artists like Coïncidence, Remy Dubois, Luc Pilartz, Rue du Village and Claude Flagel have kept the folk traditions alive.	 	 <strong>Chanson</strong>	 	 The greatest Belgian chansonnier was Jacques Brel, whose classic songs have been covered by several international artists such as David Bowie, Frank Sinatra, Scott Walker and Terry Jacks. Others like Salvatore Adamo, Pierre Rapsat, Arno, Maurane, Axelle Red and Lara Fabian have also enjoyed some success in other French-speaking countries.	 	 <strong>Po')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(186,'186','11/10/2009','Mireille Mathieu (born July 22, 1946) is a French singer, who besides being very successful in her own country, became a star of international stature, recording in several languages.  	 She was born in Avignon, Vaucluse, France, the oldest daughter of a poor family of fourteen children. She began singing as a small child, appearing in public at the age of four, singing in her church. As a young girl she worked in a factory, where she saved her money to pay for singing lessons.  ','<strong>Mireille Mathieu</strong> (born July 22, 1946) is a French singer, who besides being very successful in her own country, became a star of international stature, recording in several languages.	 	 	 She was born in Avignon, Vaucluse, France, the oldest daughter of a poor family of fourteen children. She began singing as a small child, appearing in public at the age of four, singing in her church. As a young girl she worked in a factory, where she saved her money to pay for singing lessons.	 	 Discovered by Johnny Stark, manager of France%27s biggest star at the time, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Johnny+Hallyday">Johnny Hallyday</a>, she was tutored by orchestra leader <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Paul+Mauriat">Paul Mauriat</a> and song writer André Pascal who wrote &quot;Mon crédo&quot;, &quot;Viens dans ma rue&quot;, &quot;La première étoile&quot; and many other hits for her . After her television performance in 1965 and debut run at the Paris Olympia, she was immediately hailed as the next <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%C3%89dith+Piaf?q=%C3%89dith+Piaf">Édith Piaf</a>, such was her haunting voice.	 	 Singles such as &quot;Mon Credo&quot; and &quot;C%27est Ton Nom&quot; made her a huge star in France and all over Europe while making her a big success in North America and Mexico. Her French cover of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Engelbert+Humperdinck">Engelbert Humperdinck</a>%27s &quot;The Last Waltz&quot; generated much publicity in Great Britain and with hit after hit, she soon toured Canada and the United States where she appeared on the Ed Sullivan Show and the Danny Kaye Show. In Las Vegas, she sang with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Dean+Martin">Dean Martin</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Frank+Sinatra">Frank Sinatra</a> to great applause.	 	 Still much in demand, she continues to perform regularly. She travels frequently, appearing at such venues as New York City%27s Carnegie Hall, Sport Palace in Montreal, Universal Amphitheatre in Los Angeles and Ice Palace of St. Petersburg. She has sold about 150 million copies of her albums in her 40 year career, recorded about 1200 songs in 9 languages, and was the first western singer in history who gave concerts in China. Over the years she sang duets with such luminaries as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Charles+Aznavour">Charles Aznavour</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Barry+Manilow">Barry Manilow</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Paul+Anka">Paul Anka</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Pl%C3%A1cido+Domingo">Plácido Domingo</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Julio+Iglesias">Julio Iglesias</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Tom+Jones">Tom Jones</a> and others.	 	 Songs such as &quot;Acropolis adieu,&quot; &quot;Ne me quitte pas,&quot; and &quot;Santa Maria de la mer,&quot; are considered classics. Her French version of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Roy+Orbison">Roy Orbison</a>%27s ballad, &quot;Blue Bayou&quot;, is regarded by many as one of the best covers of that popular song.	 	 In 1989, President François Mitterrand invited Mireille Mathieu to sing a tribute to General de Gaulle. She gave a series of concerts at the Palais des Congrès in Paris in December 1990. Three years later, she released an album devoted to her all-time idol, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%C3%89dith+Piaf?q=%C3%89dith+Piaf">Édith Piaf</a>.	 	 In January 1996, &quot;Vous lui direz…&quot; was released. Maxime le Forestier wrote one of the titles, &quot;A la moitié de la distance&quot;. She did not choose to perform live in France to promote the album, preferring rather to go to Los Angeles USA, where she triumphed on November 14th with her vibrant tribute to another of her idols, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Judy+Garland">Judy Garland</a>. The performance was a tremendous success she was dressed by Provence couturier, Christian Lacroix and looked stunning for the performance. [1]	 	 In 2002, she released her 37th French albu')

It also saw a major rise in protest songs  and the folk genre. Pioneers in the US were Bob Dylan, The Mamas and the Papas, and Joan Baez; in England, Donovan helped create the folk rock sound.')

He is only two years old when his family is leaving their village to establish themselves in Tilleur, Wallony, near Liege, a little county in Belgium. He did inherit his fondness of music and singing from his father Peppino. When he is 12 years old he decides to buy his first guitar and joines the band Les Eperviers. His father is approving this decision by helping hom to acced at the Music Accademy. This is a succesful thing to do, because Frederic Francois is winning that same year the singing contest “Festival du Chatelet”, which allows him to make his first record. But he is making his real debut in 1969 when he makes his first 45 tours record whith his actual nickname. He gets married and have a family of his own while he is still young. This thing happens in 1971, the year when his first hits are launched, such like “Je n’ai jamais aime comme je t’aime”, “Laisse-moi vivre ma vie”, “Chicago” and many others. As a tribute to his increasing charismatical success in France, he also conquered by his music Canada, Belgium and the Switzerland. The hits are still going on with titles like ” Mon coeur te dit Je t’aime” in 1984 and ” Je t’aime a l’itallienne” in 1985. Many times till now Frederic Francois is performing many concerts in the Olympia Hall in Paris, such as in the years 1994, 1996, 1998 or 2000. If the name of Frederick Francois is mostly related to the 70’s decade, he still has a great fame and huge success especially among the French music listeners. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(311,'311','20/09/2008','Belgium is a cultural crossroads where Flemish Dutch-speaking and Walloon French-speaking inhabitants mix with German minorities and immigrant communities from Republic of the Congo and other distant countries.  Classical music  During the centuries Belgium produced several notable names in the field of classical music. In the 15th and 16th century composers like Guillaume Dufay, Orlando di Lasso, Josquin des Prez reached European acclaim. André Ernest Modeste Grétry was the most famous composer- born in what is now called Belgium- of the 18th century.','Belgium is a cultural crossroads where Flemish Dutch-speaking and Walloon French-speaking inhabitants mix with German minorities and immigrant communities from Republic of the Congo and other distant countries.	 	 <strong>Classical music</strong>	 	 During the centuries Belgium produced several notable names in the field of classical music. In the 15th and 16th century composers like Guillaume Dufay, Orlando di Lasso, Josquin des Prez reached European acclaim. André Ernest Modeste Grétry was the most famous composer- born in what is now called Belgium- of the 18th century. The 19th century supplied composers like Henri Vieuxtemps, César Franck, Guillaume Lekeu and Eugène Ysaÿe. The famous German composer Ludwig van Beethoven was of Flemish descent and his grandfather (who was born in Mechelen). At the end of the 20th century the most notable Belgian composer was Wim Mertens.	 	 In the field of opera, baritons Jules Bastin and José van Dam have become the most famous and internationally successful Belgian opera singers. In the lighter classical genre Flemish singer Helmut Lotti reached huge international success with his interpretations of popular opera songs for large audiences.	 	 <strong>Blues and Jazz</strong>	 	 One of the most famous jazz instruments, the saxophone, was invented by a Belgian: Adolphe Sax.	 	 Some known Belgian blues artists are Elmore D (who sings in English and Walloon dialect), the Flemish Roland van Campenhout (also known as Roland) and the Brussels band Tomahawk Blues Band.	 	 In the 1930s, the Belgian gypsy guitarist Django Reinhardt became one of the first important jazz musicians to be born in Europe, and one of the most important jazz guitarists of all time. In 1949 Toots Thielemans joined a jam session in Paris with Sidney Bechet, Charlie Parker, Miles Davis, Max Roach and others. He moved to the US in 1952 where he was a member of Charlie Parker%27s All-Stars. Toots Thielemans is often credited by jazz aficionados and jazz critics of being the greatest jazz mouth hamonica player of the century. His music has been used in films like Midnight Cowboy and Turkish Delight, and television series such as Sesame Street and Baantjer. Other wellknown Belgian artists are Aka Moon, Bobby Jaspar, Bert Joris, Philip Catherine, Steve Houben, Octurn and René Thomas	 	 <strong>Folk and other traditional music</strong>	 	 Bobbejaan Schoepen has been a pioneer in Belgian vaudeville and popmusic since the late 1940s. Not only was he the first Belgian singer to manage an international breakthrough, he was also the first to use modern equipment, a personal tourbus and a system of artist sponsoring. He also introduced the first country &amp; western recordings in the Low Countries and Germany. In the 1950s Bobbejaan Schoepen recorded his own absolutely crazy folk music often singing in the dialect of his native Brussels. He is also a virtuoso whistler.	 	 During the 1950s and following decades the most popular, enduring, commercial and critical successful Flemish singer was Will Tura, whose most well known hit in Flanders is &quot;Ik ben zo eenzaam zonder jou&quot; (1963) (&quot;I%27m so lonely without you&quot;).	 	 The most popular and enduring artists in Flanders and the Netherlands who sing in either their Flemish dialect or standard Dutch are Eddy Wally, Raymond van het Groenewoud, De Kreuners, Clouseau, Gorki (band), Noordkaap and de Fixkes.	 	 Walloon folk music has not had as vibrant a revival as Flemish, but artists like Coïncidence, Remy Dubois, Luc Pilartz, Rue du Village and Claude Flagel have kept the folk traditions alive.	 	 <strong>Chanson</strong>	 	 The greatest Belgian chansonnier was Jacques Brel, whose classic songs have been covered by several international artists such as David Bowie, Frank Sinatra, Scott Walker and Terry Jacks. Others like Salvatore Adamo, Pierre Rapsat, Arno, Maurane, Axelle Red and Lara Fabian have also enjoyed some success in other French-speaking countries.	 	 <strong>Po')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(400,'400','01/11/2010','Humour is the tendency of particular cognitive experiences to provoke laughter and provide amusement. Many theories exist about what humour is and what social function it serves. People of most ages and cultures respond to humour. The majority of people are able to be amused, to laugh or smile at something funny, and thus they are considered to have a %27sense of humour%27.  The term derives from the humoural medicine of the ancient Greeks, which stated that a mix of fluids known as humours (Greek: ?????, chymos, literally juice or sap; metaphorically, flavour) controlled human health and emotion.','Humour is the tendency of particular cognitive experiences to provoke laughter and provide amusement. Many theories exist about what humour is and what social function it serves. People of most ages and cultures respond to humour. The majority of people are able to be amused, to laugh or smile at something funny, and thus they are considered to have a %27sense of humour%27.	 	 The term derives from the humoural medicine of the ancient Greeks, which stated that a mix of fluids known as humours (Greek: ?????, chymos, literally juice or sap; metaphorically, flavour) controlled human health and emotion.	 	 A sense of humour is the ability to experience humour, although the extent to which an individual will find something humorous depends on a host of variables, including geographical location, culture, maturity, level of education, intelligence, and context. For example, young children may possibly favour slapstick, such as Punch and Judy puppet shows or cartoons (e.g., Tom and Jerry). Satire may rely more on understanding the target of the humour, and thus tends to appeal to more mature audiences. Nonsatirical humour can be specifically termed %27recreational drollery%27.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(533,'533','02/03/2011','Indie pop is a genre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/alternative%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">alternative rock</a> music that originated in the United Kingdom in the mid 19<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/80s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">80s</a>, with its roots in the Scottish <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-punk</a> bands on the <a href="http://www.last.fm/label/Postcard/" class="bbcode_label">Postcard</a> Records label in the early %2780s such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Orange+Juice" class="bbcode_artist">Orange Juice</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Josef+K" class="bbcode_artist">Josef K</a> and the dominant UK independent band of the mid eighties, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/The+Smiths" class="bbcode_artist">The Smiths</a>.  While the term ‘indie’ had been used for some time to describe artists on independent labels (and the labels themselves), the key moment in the naming of the genre was the release of NME%27s C86 tape in 1986.','<strong>Indie pop</strong> is a genre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/alternative%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">alternative rock</a> music that originated in the <a href="http://www.last.fm/place/United+Kingdom" class="bbcode_place">United Kingdom</a> in the mid 19<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/80s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">80s</a>, with its roots in the Scottish <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-punk</a> bands on the <a href="http://www.last.fm/label/Postcard/" class="bbcode_label">Postcard</a> Records label in the early %2780s such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Orange+Juice" class="bbcode_artist">Orange Juice</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Josef+K" class="bbcode_artist">Josef K</a> and the dominant UK independent band of the mid eighties, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/The+Smiths" class="bbcode_artist">The Smiths</a>.	 	 While the term <em>‘indie’</em> had been used for some time to describe artists on independent labels (and the labels themselves), the key moment in the naming of the genre was the release of NME%27s C86 tape in 1986. Although featuring a wide range of bands including <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Primal+Scream" class="bbcode_artist">Primal Scream</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bogshed" class="bbcode_artist">Bogshed</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Half+Man+Half+Biscuit" class="bbcode_artist">Half Man Half Biscuit</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/The+Wedding+Present" class="bbcode_artist">The Wedding Present</a>, it over time became shorthand for a genre known by a variety of terms. Initially it was dubbed %27C86%27 (after the tape itself), the more ambiguous indie pop, Cutie or a term coined by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/John+Peel" class="bbcode_artist">John Peel</a>: shambling bands. Retrospectively, especially in the <a href="http://www.last.fm/place/United+States" class="bbcode_place">United States</a>, the terms <strong>twee</strong> and <strong>twee pop</strong> were used, initially ironically, due to what commentators called the &quot;revolt into childhood&quot; of its followers.	 	 Musically its key characteristics were jangling guitars, a love of sixties pop and often fey, innocent lyrics. The UK label <a href="http://www.last.fm/label/Sarah/" class="bbcode_label">Sarah</a> Records and its most popular band <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/The+Field+Mice" class="bbcode_artist">The Field Mice</a>, although more diverse than the label indicates, were probably its most typical proponents. It was also inspired by the DIY scene of punk and there was a thriving fanzine, label and club and gig circuit. Scenes later developed in the United States particularly around labels such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/label/K/" class="bbcode_label">K</a> Records. Genres such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/riot%20grrrl" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">riot grrrl</a> and bands as diverse as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Nirvana" class="bbcode_artist">Nirvana</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Manic+Street+Preachers" class="bbcode_artist">Manic Street Preachers</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Belle+and+Sebastian" class="bbcode_artist">Belle and Sebastian</a> have all acknowledged its influence.	 	 In the mid to late 80s, indie pop was criticized for its tweeness and underachievement but many now argue that C86 and the birth of the genre was a pivotal moment for independent music in the UK. It continues to have a strong following and inspire musicians, not just in the UK but around the world with new labels, clubs and bands devoted to the sound.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(539,'539','24/12/2010','Indie is a particular sound that has little to do with past associations of independent music. Indie also encapsulates a musical philosophy. Many artists utilize alternative instrumentation, jangling guitars, and may borrow from disparate genres such as folk, dance rock, and hip hop.   The term %27indie%27 is best known as being an abbreviation for the word %27independent%27. This term was once used to differentiate between bands that were on a major record label and those that weren%27t.','Indie is a particular sound that has little to do with past associations of independent music. Indie also encapsulates a musical philosophy. Many artists utilize alternative instrumentation, jangling guitars, and may borrow from disparate genres such as folk, dance rock, and hip hop. 	 	 The term %27indie%27 is best known as being an abbreviation for the word %27independent%27. This term was once used to differentiate between bands that were on a major record label and those that weren%27t. It also differentiates between an %27independent%27 sound and type of music and the more typical top-40 sound that was so prevalent during the 1980s. For example, many of the hair bands and hard rock scene had become very typical in musical composition (melody, chorus, melody, bridge, chorus, etc.). %27Indie%27 music may or may not follow this pattern.	 	 For these reasons, in recent years the term %27indie%27 has been applied to bands that have rock sound but aren%27t on a major record label. Bands like Coldplay, The Killers and Razorlight are not classified as being %27indie%27 because of this. On the other hand, bands such as Radiohead (who are no longer on a major record label), Pavement, Belle And Sebastian, and Joy Division can be classed as indie using the &quot;independent sound&quot; meaning.	 	 This term is wildly disputed on last.fm as well as on plenty of forums. People tag everything from Katy Perry to Meat Puppets as being %27indie%27. You may even find some of your trve kvlt black metal bands appearing with an indie tag. As long as they aren%27t on a major record label. This spectrum of tagging shows the depth and arguably the inconsistency of the label. 	 ')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(545,'545','17/08/2010','Deeply rooted in <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic death metal</a> with lyrics centered around Viking history and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norse_mythology" rel="nofollow">Norse mythology</a>. Amon Amarth (formerly known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Scum" class="bbcode_artist">Scum</a>) was formed, with the arrival of Johan Hegg as the new vocalist, in 1992 in Tumba, Sweden, a southern suburb of Stockholm. They began writing material with lots of melodies, harmonies and lyrics about Vikings and the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norse_gods" rel="nofollow">norse Pantheon</a>. In summer 1993 they entered Lagret Studio to record the <a title="Amon Amarth - Thor Arise" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Amon+Amarth/Thor+Arise" class="bbcode_album">Thor Arise</a> demo, which would later on appear on the bonus disc of the album <a title="Amon Amarth - Versus The World" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Amon+Amarth/Versus+The+World" class="bbcode_album">Versus The World</a>.','Deeply rooted in <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic death metal</a> with lyrics centered around Viking history and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norse_mythology" rel="nofollow">Norse mythology</a>. <strong>Amon Amarth</strong> (formerly known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Scum" class="bbcode_artist">Scum</a>) was formed, with the arrival of Johan Hegg as the new vocalist, in 1992 in Tumba, Sweden, a southern suburb of <span title="Unknown place" class="bbcode_unknown">Stockholm</span>. They began writing material with lots of melodies, harmonies and lyrics about Vikings and the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norse_gods" rel="nofollow">norse Pantheon</a>. In summer 1993 they entered Lagret Studio to record the <a title="Amon Amarth - Thor Arise" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Amon+Amarth/Thor+Arise" class="bbcode_album">Thor Arise</a> demo, which would later on appear on the bonus disc of the album <a title="Amon Amarth - Versus The World" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Amon+Amarth/Versus+The+World" class="bbcode_album">Versus The World</a>. The band continued rehearsing and writing stronger material and again entered the studio. The result was the second demo, <a title="Amon Amarth - The Arrival of the Fimbul Winter" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Amon+Amarth/The+Arrival+of+the+Fimbul+Winter" class="bbcode_album">The Arrival of the Fimbul Winter</a>. This time the band was much more satisfied with the sound and songs and launched it to an unsuspecting underground. The response was overwhelming, quickly selling out of the first pressing and secured them a one off deal with <a href="http://www.last.fm/place/Singapore" class="bbcode_place">Singapore</a>%27s <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Pulverised" class="bbcode_label">Pulverised</a> Records.	 	 This time they decided to use Abyss Studio, owned by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Peter+T%C3%A4gtgren" class="bbcode_artist">Peter T&auml;gtgren</a> of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Hypocrisy" class="bbcode_artist">Hypocrisy</a>, and during five days in November 1995 the MCD <a title="Amon Amarth - Sorrow Throughout the Nine Worlds" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Amon+Amarth/Sorrow+Throughout+the+Nine+Worlds" class="bbcode_album">Sorrow Throughout the Nine Worlds</a> was recorded. The five track recording contained three new songs plus two re-recorded tracks from the band%27s second demo. The MCD was released in April 1996 and continued the band%27s build to world dominance. June 1996 saw the exiting of drummer Nico who was quickly replaced with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Martin+Lopez" class="bbcode_artist">Martin Lopez</a>. During this time labels began to show interest and after much consideration the band chose to sign with <a href="http://www.last.fm/label/Metal+Blade/" class="bbcode_label">Metal Blade</a>.	 	 In March 1997, <strong>Amon Amarth</strong> again entered Abyss Studios to record their <a href="http://www.last.fm/label/Metal+Blade/" class="bbcode_label">Metal Blade</a> debut <a title="Amon Amarth - Once Sent From The Golden Hall" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Amon+Amarth/Once+Sent+From+The+Golden+Hall" class="bbcode_album">Once Sent From The Golden Hall</a> with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Peter+T%C3%A4gtgren" class="bbcode_artist">Peter T&auml;gtgren</a>. The result proved that they were destined to become a force of fury in the Swedish <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a> scene and beyond.	 	 After the recording of this album, guitarist <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Anders+Hansson" class="bbcode_artist">Anders Hansson</a> quit just a month before their first major tour with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Deicide" class="bbcode_artist">Deicide</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Six+Feet+Under" class="bbcode_artist">Six Feet Under</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Brutal+Truth" class="bbcode_')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(575,'575','30/11/2010','Melodic death metal (also referred to as melodeath) is a subgenre of metal which combines the melody of the New Wave of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/british%20heavy%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">british heavy metal</a> (NWOBHM) with the intensity of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a>. The genre is also known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/gothenburg%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">gothenburg metal</a>, a reference to the city in Sweden where it originated. Originally the genre combined the harmony style and groove melodies of heavy metal with the harsh thrashing sound and vocals of death metal. Early melodic metal bands seem to have taken lots of influence from American bands ','Melodic death metal (also referred to as melodeath) is a subgenre of metal which combines the melody of the New Wave of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/british%20heavy%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">british heavy metal</a> (NWOBHM) with the intensity of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a>. The genre is also known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/gothenburg%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">gothenburg metal</a>, a reference to the city in Sweden where it originated. Originally the genre combined the harmony style and groove melodies of heavy metal with the harsh thrashing sound and vocals of death metal. Early melodic metal bands seem to have taken lots of influence from American bands	 	 Melodic death metal contains more melodic guitar riffs, melodic solos, and acoustic guitar work than death metal. It also contains more comprehensible lyrics with traditional death growl and screaming vocals. The pioneers of melodic death metal include <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Ceremonial+Oath" class="bbcode_artist">Ceremonial Oath</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Carcass" class="bbcode_artist">Carcass</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Dark+Tranquillity" class="bbcode_artist">Dark Tranquillity</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/At+the+Gates" class="bbcode_artist">At the Gates</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/In+Flames" class="bbcode_artist">In Flames</a>. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Sentenced" class="bbcode_artist">Sentenced</a> is also sometimes credited as one of the first melodic death metal bands with their release of <span title="Unknown album" class="bbcode_unknown">North From Here</span>. Some melodic death metal bands combine the genre with other metal genres such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/progressive%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">progressive metal</a> (e.g. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Into+Eternity" class="bbcode_artist">Into Eternity</a>), <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/power%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">power metal</a> (e.g. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Children+of+Bodom" class="bbcode_artist">Children of Bodom</a>), <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/symphonic%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">symphonic metal</a> (e.g. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Eternal+Tears+of+Sorrow" class="bbcode_artist">Eternal Tears of Sorrow</a>), <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/thrash%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">thrash metal</a> (e.g. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Arch+Enemy" class="bbcode_artist">Arch Enemy</a>), <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/doom%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">doom metal</a> (e.g. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Swallow+the+Sun" class="bbcode_artist">Swallow the Sun</a>) and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/folk%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">folk metal</a> (e.g. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Eluveitie" class="bbcode_artist">Eluveitie</a>).	 	 In the late 1990s, many melodic death metal bands changed their style of playing by adding more melodic elements; more melodic choruses and riffs and making more prominent use of keyboards. Also many melodic death metal bands moved away from the lyrical themes of death, gore, and murder common in other death metal groups.')

Arrangements are usually more complex than the somewhat simple early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a> that originated in Norway in the early 1990s and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/folk%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">folk metal</a> is often mixed in, though it%27s not a necessity by any means.','Viking metal evolved from <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a>. Arrangements are usually more complex than the somewhat simple early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a> that originated in Norway in the early 1990s and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/folk%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">folk metal</a> is often mixed in, though it%27s not a necessity by any means. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(581,'581','23/12/2010','Death metal is a subgenre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metal</a>, most easily identifiable by its utilization of bass-heavy guitar distortion, harsh, often growled or grunted vocals, and particular brand of compositional density.  Better known death metal bands include <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Morbid+Angel" class="bbcode_artist">Morbid Angel</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Autopsy" class="bbcode_artist">Autopsy</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Suffocation" class="bbcode_artist">Suffocation</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Entombed" class="bbcode_artist">Entombed</a>, all of which had in their earliest years contributed codifying releases to the subgenre.  In the middle of the 1980s...','Death metal is a subgenre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metal</a>, most easily identifiable by its utilization of bass-heavy guitar distortion, harsh, often growled or grunted vocals, and particular brand of compositional density.  Better known death metal bands include <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Morbid+Angel" class="bbcode_artist">Morbid Angel</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Autopsy" class="bbcode_artist">Autopsy</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Suffocation" class="bbcode_artist">Suffocation</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Entombed" class="bbcode_artist">Entombed</a>, all of which had in their earliest years contributed codifying releases to the subgenre.	 	 In the middle of the 1980s, the stylistic origins of death metal manifested; 1984 saw the release of a few EPs (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Slayer" class="bbcode_artist">Slayer</a> - <em><a title="Slayer - Haunting the Chapel" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Slayer/Haunting+the+Chapel" class="bbcode_album">Haunting the Chapel</a></em>; <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Celtic+Frost" class="bbcode_artist">Celtic Frost</a> - <em><a title="Celtic Frost - Morbid Tales" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Celtic+Frost/Morbid+Tales" class="bbcode_album">Morbid Tales</a></em>) and several demos (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Necrophagia" class="bbcode_artist">Necrophagia</a> - <em>Death Is Fun</em>; <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Possessed" class="bbcode_artist">Possessed</a> - <em>Death Metal</em>) from which the subgenre would initially draw its compositional and lyrical motifs.  1985 saw the first full-length death metal release in the well-known <em><a title="Possessed - Seven Churches" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Possessed/Seven+Churches" class="bbcode_album">Seven Churches</a></em>, the earliest identifiable distinction the subgenre made from other emergent forms of extreme metal.	 	 By the end of the decade, death metal had developed regional specificities.  Two particular regions of the United States yielded two particular sounds: California (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Sadus" class="bbcode_artist">Sadus</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Terrorizer" class="bbcode_artist">Terrorizer</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Autopsy" class="bbcode_artist">Autopsy</a>) and Florida (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Obituary" class="bbcode_artist">Obituary</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Morbid+Angel" class="bbcode_artist">Morbid Angel</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Death" class="bbcode_artist">Death</a>); meanwhile, Sweden had developed a <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/swedish%20death%20metal">unified sound of its own</a> (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Merciless" class="bbcode_artist">Merciless</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Grotesque" class="bbcode_artist">Grotesque</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Carnage" class="bbcode_artist">Carnage</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Nihilist" class="bbcode_artist">Nihilist</a>).  Other regions of the world followed suit, to include Brazil (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Psychic+Possessor" class="bbcode_artist">Psychic Possessor</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Mutilator" class="bbcode_artist">Mutilator</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Sepultura" class="bbcode_artist">Sepultura</a>), Britain (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Cancer" class="bbcode_artist">Cancer</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Benediction" class="bbcode_artist">Benediction</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bolt+Thrower" class="bbcode_artist">Bolt Thrower</a>), and Mainland Europe (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Necrodeath" class="bbcode_artist">Necrodeath</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Messiah" class="bbcode_artist">Messiah</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Pestilence" class="bbcode_artist">Pestilence</a>).	 	 1990 saw a worldwide surge of activity in death metal.  Further subgenres were founded by')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(584,'584','06/02/2011','&quot;Heavy metal&quot; (often referred to simply as metal) is a subgenre of rock music that developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s. With roots in blues-rock and psychedelic rock, the bands that created heavy metal developed a thick, massive sound, characterized by highly amplified distortion and extended guitar solos. Allmusic states that “of all rock &amp; roll’s myriad forms, heavy metal is the most extreme in terms of volume, machismo, and theatricality.”  ','&quot;<em>Heavy metal</em>&quot; (often referred to simply as metal) is a subgenre of rock music that developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s. With roots in blues-rock and psychedelic rock, the bands that created heavy metal developed a thick, massive sound, characterized by highly amplified distortion and extended guitar solos. Allmusic states that “of all rock &amp; roll’s myriad forms, heavy metal is the most extreme in terms of volume, machismo, and theatricality.”	 	 Heavy metal has long had a worldwide following of fans known as “metalheads” or “headbangers”. Although early heavy metal bands such as Black Sabbath, Led Zeppelin, and Deep Purple attracted large audiences, they were often critically reviled at the time, a status common throughout the history of the genre. In the mid-1970s, Judas Priest helped spur the genre’s evolution by discarding much of its blues influence. Bands in the New Wave of British Heavy Metal such as Iron Maiden and Motörhead followed in a similar vein, introducing a punk rock sensibility and an increasing emphasis on speed.	 	 In the mid-1980s, pop-infused glam metal became a major commercial force with groups like Mötley Crüe. Underground scenes produced an array of more extreme, aggressive styles: thrash metal broke into the mainstream with bands such as Metallica, also leading the development of more extreme styles, such as death metal and black metal, which remain subcultural phenomena. <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/alternative%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">alternative metal</a> later followed these, as a reaction to both: being more accessible than the extreme styles typified by death metal (while not as overtly commercial as hair metal) while also being musically varied and sonically adventurous. Since the mid-1990s, popular styles such as nu metal, which often incorporates elements of funk and hip hop; and metalcore, which blends extreme metal with hardcore punk, have further expanded the definition of the genre.	 	 Other subgenres of metal include power metal, speed metal, melodic death metal (also known as Gothenburg metal), Industrial metal, nu-metal, thrash metal, black metal, doom metal, death metal, progressive metal and folk metal.')

The songs were sent to several record labels, and Lifeforce Records was the first to offer the band a record deal. The band%27s first self-titled MCD came out in the summer of 1998.','<strong>1 - <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a> band, formed in Germany in 1997</strong>	 2 -Folk Duo	 =============================	 	 1 - <strong>Caliban</strong>, a <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a> band, was formed in Germany in 1997 under the name <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Never+Again" class="bbcode_artist">Never Again</a>. After 6 months of playing together, the band recorded their first two songs for a compilation, which was never released. The songs were sent to several record labels, and Lifeforce Records was the first to offer the band a record deal. The band%27s first self-titled MCD came out in the summer of 1998. To promote the CD, Caliban played many shows all over Europe and a few support shows for bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Morning+Again" class="bbcode_artist">Morning Again</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Earth+Crisis" class="bbcode_artist">Earth Crisis</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Cro-Mags" class="bbcode_artist">Cro-Mags</a>.	 	 After their European tour, in 1999 Caliban entered the studio to record their first full-length CD, entitled <a title="Caliban - A Small Boy And A Grey Heaven" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Caliban/A+Small+Boy+And+A+Grey+Heaven" class="bbcode_album">A Small Boy And A Grey Heaven</a>. The CD received favorable reviews in many big zines and many smaller hardcore and metal zines. The band was described as a mixture of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Slayer" class="bbcode_artist">Slayer</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Poison+the+Well" class="bbcode_artist">Poison the Well</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Hatebreed" class="bbcode_artist">Hatebreed</a>.	 	 <a title="Caliban - Vent" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Caliban/Vent" class="bbcode_album">Vent</a> came out in April 2001. Vent was released by Imperium Records and by Howling-Bull Records in Japan. Shortly after the release, Caliban was offered the opportunity to tour Japan to play the Beast-Feast 2001 in the Yokohama Arena, sharing stage with bands including <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Slayer" class="bbcode_artist">Slayer</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Pantera" class="bbcode_artist">Pantera</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Machine+Head" class="bbcode_artist">Machine Head</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Biohazard" class="bbcode_artist">Biohazard</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Morbid+Angel" class="bbcode_artist">Morbid Angel</a>. The Japan trip was followed by a US tour with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bloodjinn" class="bbcode_artist">Bloodjinn</a>, which was interrupted by the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks.	 	 In August 2002 Caliban recorded their third official release <a title="Caliban - Shadow Hearts" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Caliban/Shadow+Hearts" class="bbcode_album">Shadow Hearts</a>. This record was more melodic and harmonic than its predecessors. In 2004 the band got a record deal with Roadrunner Records and started to record their fourth album, <a title="Caliban - The Opposite From Within" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Caliban/The+Opposite+From+Within" class="bbcode_album">The Opposite From Within</a>, alongside famous producer Andy Sneap.	 	 In July 2005 the band again made a record with their friends from <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Heaven+Shall+Burn" class="bbcode_artist">Heaven Shall Burn</a> called The Split Program II.	 	 In February 2006 the band released the album <a title="Caliban - The Undying Darkness" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Caliban/The+Undying+Darkness" class="bbcode_album">The Undying Darkness</a>. It was produced by Anders Friden, the vocalist of In Flames.	 	 In May 2007 the band released <a title="Caliban - The Awakening" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Caliban/The+Awakening" class="bbcode_album">The Awakening</a>. They are using 7 string guitars and less clean vocals in t')

This later evolved in the mid <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/90s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">90s</a>, when bands began to take cues from <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic death metal</a> bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/At+the+Gates" class="bbcode_artist">At the Gates</a>, while still retaining their hardcore punk attitude and stance. Early examples of Metalcore, or what some might consider <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metallic%20hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metallic hardcore</a> include <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Integrity" class="bbcode_artist">Integrity</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Earth+Crisis" class="bbcode_artist">Earth Crisis</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Disembodied" class="bbcode_artist">Disembodied</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Converge" class="bbcode_artist">Converge</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Overcast" class="bbcode_artist">Overcast</a>. This later evolved in the mid <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/90s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">90s</a>, when bands began to take cues from <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic death metal</a> bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/At+the+Gates" class="bbcode_artist">At the Gates</a>, while still retaining their hardcore punk attitude and stance. Early examples of Metalcore, or what some might consider <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metallic%20hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metallic hardcore</a> include <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Integrity" class="bbcode_artist">Integrity</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Earth+Crisis" class="bbcode_artist">Earth Crisis</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Disembodied" class="bbcode_artist">Disembodied</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Converge" class="bbcode_artist">Converge</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Overcast" class="bbcode_artist">Overcast</a>. 	 	 Metalcore itself has its own offshoots and derivatives such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic death metal</a> infused <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic metalcore</a>, technical <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/mathcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">mathcore</a>, and the fusion of metalcore with death metal known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/deathcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">deathcore</a> which has become a huge trend in recent years . There are also a number of bands who mix Metalcore influences with <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/groove%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">groove metal</a>; taking cues from <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Pantera" class="bbcode_artist">Pantera</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-hardcore</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/progressive%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">progressive metal</a>, or even classic <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/heavy%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">heavy metal</a> influences in some cases. 	 	 More recent and commercially successful bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Killswitch+Engage" class="bbcode_artist">Killswitch Engage</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Trivium" class="bbcode_artist">Trivium</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bullet+for+My+Valentine" class="bbcode_artist">Bullet for My Valentine</a> tend to stray more towards metal or even pop rock, with cleaner, more melodic vocals and guitar. This may have been a factor in the classification of Metalcore as a mainstream trend. With %27<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock</a>%27 and %27<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop rock</a>%27 fans being attracted to the more mainstream sound, rather than the heavy, fast riffs and screaming vocals of past bands. 	 	 Metalcore has gained a very big following, but also had its fair share of critics on both the punk and metal sides of the spectrum. The genre was launched into the mainstream with bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Atreyu" class="bbcode_artist">Atreyu</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bullet+for+My+Valentine" class="bbcode_artist">Bullet for My Valentine</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Killswitch+Engage" class="bbcode_artist">Killswitch Engage</a>, although in recent years it has declined in popularity. She felt a strange attraction to murky things, mingled with an irrepressible aspiration for beauty. So great was her enthusiasm that she began to write songs and even sang them. The world of &quot;Prenez garde aux flots bleus&quot; took shape. Strangely enough, she always sang too high for her range... So she asked Pascale Vevloet, whose the pure and delightful voice delighted her ears, to sing those ethereal tunes. Then Pierre Louis and Brigitte Thiriart, two lyrical writers who revolve in a similar galaxy as she does, offered her made-to-measure lyrics she hastened to set to music. Unexpectedly, Pierre Vervloesem arrived, offering to finalize the album. He added, here and there, the magic touch of his guitars, mixed the whole thing with great mastery, and burned a disc that Lunabee cloned in great numbers. All this is now splendidly wrapped in crispy cellophane, with a beautiful underwater booklet by Thierry Mondelaers. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(756,'756','13/11/2009','Electronic music refers to music that emphasizes the use of electronic musical instruments or electronic music technology as a central aspect of the sound of the music. Historically, electronic music was considered to be any music created with the use of electronic musical instruments or electronic processing, but in modern times, that distinction has been lost because almost all recorded music today, and the majority of live music performances, depend on extensive use of electronics.','Electronic music refers to music that emphasizes the use of electronic musical instruments or electronic music technology as a central aspect of the sound of the music. Historically, electronic music was considered to be any music created with the use of electronic musical instruments or electronic processing, but in modern times, that distinction has been lost because almost all recorded music today, and the majority of live music performances, depend on extensive use of electronics. Today, the term electronic music serves to differentiate music that uses electronics as its focal point or inspiration, from music that uses electronics mainly in service of creating an intended production that may have some electronic elements in the sound but does not focus upon them.	 	 Contemporary electronic music expresses both art music forms including computer music, experimental music, musique concrète, and others; and popular music forms including multiple styles of dance music such as techno, house, trance, electro, breakbeat, drum and bass, synth pop, etc.	 	 A distinction can be made between instruments that produce sound through electromechanical means as opposed to instruments that produce sound using electronic components.	 	 Examples of electromechanical instruments are the telharmonium, Hammond organ, and the electric guitar, whereas examples of electronic instruments are a Theremin, synthesizer, and a computer.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(820,'820','27/03/2010','The term experimental music refers to the creative process that the artist goes through to create a variety of unique sounds that when mixed together create a whole new experience in music. The process of &quot;experimentation&quot; is just as important as the outcome. &quot;Experimental&quot; music could be called more of an experience as it is not made to be distributed in the main stream but rather to give you an insight of the artists%27 complex minds.  ','The term <strong>experimental</strong> music refers to the creative process that the artist goes through to create a variety of unique sounds that when mixed together create a whole new experience in music. The process of &quot;experimentation&quot; is just as important as the outcome. &quot;Experimental&quot; music could be called more of an experience as it is not made to be distributed in the main stream but rather to give you an insight of the artists%27 complex minds.	 	 &quot;Experimental&quot; implies a profound level of inventiveness that lies completely outside the traditions of music.  It is not bound by any established rules or formulas.  Many times, the outcome of the composers%27 creative efforts is unpredictable as the composer &quot;experiments&quot; with various processes and novel approaches to produce sound or contrive a listening experience.  	 	 These experiments many times give rise to new genres of music such as: industrial, noise, free jazz, electronica, tape music, noise rock, etc.  Once those genres become more established, formulaic and recycled, they no longer strictly fit the definition of experimental music.  They may become decidedly unexperimental as norms within the genre solidify.  In order to keep experimental experimental, the composer(s) must continuously discard tradition (even tradition established by other experimental composers) and create the unexpected, reimagined, and possibly, the socially unacceptable.	 	 Experimental music refers, in the English-language literature, to a compositional tradition which arose in the mid-twentieth century, applied particularly in North America to music composed in such a way that its outcome is unforeseeable. Its most famous and influential exponent was <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/John+Cage" class="bbcode_artist">John Cage</a> (Grant 2003, 174). More loosely, the term &quot;experimental&quot; is used in conjunction with genre names to describe music within specific genres that pushes against their boundaries or definitions, or else whose approach is a hybrid of disparate styles, or incorporates unorthodox, new, distinctly unique ingredients (Anon. [n.d.]a). Similarly, it has sometimes been used to describe &quot;transethnic&quot; music: the mixture of recognizable music genres. A quite distinct sense was current in the late 1950s to describe computer-controlled composition, and the term at that time also was sometimes used for electronic music and musique concrète. &quot;Experimental music&quot; has also been used in music journalism as a general term of disapprobation for music departing from traditional norms.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(823,'823','01/09/2010','Music that is thought to be highly innovative or ahead of its time. Avant-garde music necessarily pushes the boundaries of what is acceptable as &quot;music&quot; to specialists as well as to the population at large. Historically speaking, musicologists primarily use the term &quot;avant-garde music&quot; for the radical, post-1945 tendencies Modernism in several genres of art music after the death of Anton Webern in 1945. In the 1950s the term was mostly associated with serial music.','Music that is thought to be highly innovative or ahead of its time. Avant-garde music necessarily pushes the boundaries of what is acceptable as &quot;music&quot; to specialists as well as to the population at large. Historically speaking, musicologists primarily use the term &quot;avant-garde music&quot; for the radical, post-1945 tendencies Modernism in several genres of art music after the death of Anton Webern in 1945. In the 1950s the term was mostly associated with serial music. Today the term may be used to refer to any other post-1945 trend of Modernist music not definable as experimental music, and is most frequently characterized by the rejection of tonality.	 	 Avant-garde can refer to radical or innovative classical music, psychedelia and neo-psychedelia, noise, jazz, electronic music, or music that is simply unclassifiable.	 	 Serialism is a method or technique of composition (Griffiths 2001, 116) that uses a series of values to manipulate different musical elements. Serialism began primarily with Arnold Schönberg%27s twelve-tone technique, though his contemporaries were also working to establish serialism as one example of post-tonal thinking (Whittall 2008, 1). The twelve-tone technique orders the 12 notes of the chromatic scale, forming a row or series and providing a unifying basis for a composition%27s melody, harmony, structural progressions, and variations. Other types of serialism also work with sets, collections of objects, but not necessarily with fixed-order series, and extend the technique to other musical dimensions or &quot;parameters&quot; such as duration, dynamics, and timbre. This is often called integral serialism or total serialism.	 Composers such as Arnold Schönberg, Anton Webern, Alban Berg, Karlheinz Stockhausen, Pierre Boulez, Luigi Nono, Milton Babbitt, and Jean Barraqué used serial techniques of one sort or another in much of their music. Other composers such as Béla Bartók, Luciano Berio, Benjamin Britten, Aaron Copland, Olivier Messiaen, Arvo Pärt, Walter Piston, Alfred Schnittke, Dmitri Shostakovich, Igor Stravinsky, and even some jazz composers such as Yusef Lateef and Bill Evans used serial techniques in only some of their compositions or sections of compositions.	 	 Aleatoric music (also aleatory or chance music) is music in which some element of the composition is left to chance, and/or some primary element of the composed work%27s realization is left to the determination of its performer(s). The term is most often associated with procedures in which the chance element involves a relatively limited number of possibilities. The term became known to European composers through lectures by acoustician Werner Meyer-Eppler at Darmstadt International Summer Courses for New Music in the beginning of the 1950s. According to his definition, &quot;a process is said to be aleatoric [...] if its course is determined in general but depends on chance in detail&quot; (Meyer-Eppler 1957, 55).	 	 Indeterminacy in music, which was first used early in the twentieth century in the music of Charles Ives, and in the 1930s by Henry Cowell and his student John Cage beginning in 1951 (Griffiths 2001), came to refer to (mostly American) music composed by a group of composers that grew up around Cage. This group included members of the so-called New York School: Earle Brown, Morton Feldman and Christian Wolff. Others working in this way included the Scratch Orchestra in the United Kingdom (1968 until the early 1970s) and the Japanese composer Toshi Ichiyanagi (born 1933).	 	 Surrealist music uses unexpected juxtapositions, automaticism, and other surrealist techniques. Discussing Theodor Adorno, Max Paddison (1993, 90) defines surrealist music as that which &quot;juxtaposes its historically devalued fragments in a montage-like manner which enables them to yield up new meanings within a new aesthetic unity,&quot; though Lloyd Whitesell says this is Paddison%27s gloss of the term (Whitesell 2004, 118). Anne')

The style was developed by mainly African-American DJs who started experimenting with new editing techniques such as remixing, sampling and new electronic instruments like synthesizers and sequencers. The style was developed by mainly African-American DJs who started experimenting with new editing techniques such as remixing, sampling and new electronic instruments like synthesizers and sequencers. Typical to the genre is a %27%27four to the floor%27%27 beat, often a low bass and the use of recognizable instrumentation like piano chords and soulful vocals. Eventually it gained popularity in the Detroit and New York club scenes and by the late 80s in Europe. 	 	 House music is strongly influenced by elements of the early to mid 1970s soul- and funk-infused dance music style of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/disco" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">disco</a>. House music takes disco%27s use of a prominent bass drum on every beat and developed a new style by mixing in a heavy electronic synthesizer bassline, electronic drums, electronic effects, funk and pop samples, and reverb- or delay-enhanced vocals.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(905,'905','10/04/2010','IDM can refer both to Intelligent dance music (aka <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/braindance" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">braindance</a>) and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial death metal</a>. IDM is a popular name for an electronic music genre that emerged in the early 1990s at the end of the British rave era. The genre is influenced by a wide range of musical styles particularly electronic dance music such as Detroit Techno. Stylistically, IDM tends to rely upon individualistic experimentation rather than on a particular set of musical characteristics.','IDM can refer both to Intelligent dance music (aka <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/braindance" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">braindance</a>) and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial death metal</a>. IDM is a popular name for an electronic music genre that emerged in the early 1990s at the end of the British rave era. The genre is influenced by a wide range of musical styles particularly electronic dance music such as Detroit Techno. Stylistically, IDM tends to rely upon individualistic experimentation rather than on a particular set of musical characteristics. The range of post-techno styles to emerge in the early 1990s were described variously as art techno, ambient techno, intelligent techno, and electronica. In America the latter term is now used by the music industry as a catchall to describe EDM and its many derivatives.	 	 The term IDM is said to have originated in the United States in 1993 with the formation of the IDM list, an electronic mailing list originally charted for the discussion of music by (but not limited to) a number of prominent British artists, especially those appearing on a 1992 Warp Records compilation called Artificial Intelligence. The term is still seen by some as being peculiar to the U.S. but it is routinely used by music journalists, record labels, and fans on both sides of the Atlantic.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(908,'908','19/08/2010','Disco is a genre of dance-oriented music that originated in African American, gay and Hispanic American communities in 1970s. In what is considered a forerunner to disco style clubs in February 1970 New York City DJ David Mancuso opened The Loft, a members-only private dance club set in his own home. Most agree that the first disco songs were released in 1973, though some claim that Soul Makossa by <span title="Unknown artist" class="bbcode_unknown">Manu Dibango%27s</span> from 1972 to be the first disco record. The first article about disco was written in September 1973 by Vince Aletti for Rolling Stone Magazine.','Disco is a genre of dance-oriented music that originated in African American, gay and Hispanic American communities in 1970s. In what is considered a forerunner to disco style clubs in February 1970 New York City DJ David Mancuso opened The Loft, a members-only private dance club set in his own home. Most agree that the first disco songs were released in 1973, though some claim that Soul Makossa by <span title="Unknown artist" class="bbcode_unknown">Manu Dibango%27s</span> from 1972 to be the first disco record. The first article about disco was written in September 1973 by Vince Aletti for Rolling Stone Magazine. In 1974 New York City%27s WPIX-FM premiered the first disco radio show.	 	 Musical influences include funk, soul music. The disco sound has a soaring, often reverberated vocals over a steady &quot;four-on-the-floor&quot; beat, an eighth note (quaver) or sixteenth note (semi-quaver) hi-hat pattern with an open hi-hat on the off-beat, and prominent, syncopated electric bass line. Strings, horns, electric pianos, and electric guitars create a lush background sound. Orchestral instruments such as the flute are often used for solo melodies, and unlike in rock, lead guitar is rarely used.	 	 Well-known late 1970s disco performers included <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bee+Gees" class="bbcode_artist">Bee Gees</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Donna+Summer" class="bbcode_artist">Donna Summer</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/The+Jacksons" class="bbcode_artist">The Jacksons</a>. Summer would become the first well-known and most popular female disco artist, and also played a part in pioneering the electronic sound that later became a part of disco (see below). While performers and singers garnered the lion%27s share of public attention, the behind-the-scenes producers played an equal, if not more important role in disco, since they often wrote the songs and created the innovative sounds and production techniques that were part of the &quot;disco sound&quot;. Many non-disco artists recorded disco songs at the height of disco%27s popularity, and films such as Saturday Night Fever and Thank God It%27s Friday contributed to disco%27s rise in mainstream popularity and ironically the beginning of its commercial decline. The resurgence of Disco, the second generation of Disco artists, commonly referred to as &quot;Dance&quot; or &quot;Dance Pop&quot; artists took shape. By this point, this style of music no longer favoured only the highly orchestral song structure. From 1990 forward, while not commonly referred to as Disco,  continued to gain mainstream success. By the 2000s, the direct decendant of Disco, called Nu Disco also started taking shape.')

Their history dates back to 1983 and the formation of the <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Wild+Bunch" class="bbcode_artist">Wild Bunch</a>, one of the earliest and most successful sound-system/DJ collectives to arrive on the UK music scene; renowned for their seamless integration of a wide range of musical styles, from <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">punk</a> to <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/reggae" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">reggae</a> to R&amp;B, the group%27s parties quickly became can%27t-miss events for the Bristol club crowd, and at the peak of their popularity they drew crowds so enormous that the local live music scene essentially ground to a halt.	 	 When the Wild Bunch folded during the mid-%2780s, two of its members -- Andrew  Vowles (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Mushroom" class="bbcode_artist">Mushroom</a>) and Grant Marshall (<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Daddy+G" class="bbcode_artist">Daddy G</a>) -- teamed with local graffiti artist <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/3D" class="bbcode_artist">3D</a> (born Robert del Naja) to form Massive Attack in 1987; another Wild Bunch alum, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Nellee+Hooper" class="bbcode_artist">Nellee Hooper</a>, split his time between the new group and his other project, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Soul+II+Soul" class="bbcode_artist">Soul II Soul</a>. The tag isn%27t limited to Bristol-based bands though; bands as far as Canada (eg. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Perfume+Tree" class="bbcode_artist">Perfume Tree</a>) or Costa Rica (eg. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%C3%9Aztari" class="bbcode_artist">&Uacute;ztari</a>) have been considered %27trip-hop%27.
