','A &quot;type of dance music, played on electronic instruments and with a slow beat&quot;, according to Longman Dictionary, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/trip-hop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">trip-hop</a> (also known in the past as the &quot;Bristol sound&quot;) is, in fact, a musical movement that started in Bristol, UK. The tag isn%27t limited to Bristol-based bands though; bands as far as Canada (eg. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Perfume+Tree" class="bbcode_artist">Perfume Tree</a>) or Costa Rica (eg. <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%C3%9Aztari" class="bbcode_artist">&Uacute;ztari</a>) have been considered %27trip-hop%27.  Many %27trip-hop%27 bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Massive+Attack" class="bbcode_artist">Massive Attack</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Portishead" class="bbcode_artist">Portishead</a> or <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Tricky" class="bbcode_artist">Tricky</a> have denied the term though, claiming it to be &quot;an invention of media journalists&quot;. (It was in fact coined by Luke Vibert aka Wagon Christ).	 	 Trip-hop music is widely considered to be part of electronic music. However, unlike most sub-genres of electronic music, trip-hop has a mostly organic sound that rarely puts emphasis on electronic instruments. At first, bands like Portishead have been considered %27<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/alternative%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">alternative rock</a>%27 in the lack of a term like trip-hop; however, the message of most trip-hop music is different from the message of most <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock</a> music. Also, guitars aren%27t used often and, when they are used, they are used in a moderate proportion, whilst drums and vocals are the main instruments. Trip-hop couldn%27t be considered <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop</a> music, as most trip-hop music hasn%27t reached enough popularity, while popular bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Massive+Attack" class="bbcode_artist">Massive Attack</a> aren%27t associated with pop music.	 	 Trip-hop is considered to be a very abused tag, used for artists that couldn%27t be considered %27trip-hop%27. After the initial success generated by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Portishead" class="bbcode_artist">Portishead</a>%27s Dummy album, in the mid-/late %2790s discussion took place on the subject of so-called %27trip-hop%27 bands using the Portishead formula without presenting enough innovations to be considered not clones. In reality, very few bands replicated the exact Portishead sound; there were many pop-oriented bands who didn%27t used the %27cabaret noir%27 elements of the Portishead sound, for instance, often resulting in a sound that resembles <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Morcheeba" class="bbcode_artist">Morcheeba</a> or <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Hooverphonic" class="bbcode_artist">Hooverphonic</a>. Even so, many such bands presented special elements or contributions that made them overcome the %27Portishead clone%27 tag and enter the ranks of trip-hop databases such as <a href="http://tripofagia.sites.uol.com.br/tripofagia-1024-en.htm" rel="nofollow">Tripofagia</a> or <a href="http://www.tripnotic.de/" rel="nofollow">Tripnotic</a>.	 	 At most of the artists/bands of this movement, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hip-hop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hip-hop</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/dub" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">dub</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/reggae" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">reggae</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/techno" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">techno</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock</a>and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop</a> could be identified. However, being a musical movement, not a fully fleshed out sub-genre, it is hard to identify a recipe for all trip-hop artists. Most comm')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1051,'1051','25/05/2010','Chill out (sometimes also chillout, chill-out, or simply chill), a term derived from a slang injunction to relax, emerged in the early and mid-1990s as a catch-all term for various styles of relatively mellow, slow-tempo music made by contemporary producers in the electronic music scene. The term &quot;Chill out music&quot;, as well as the genre itself, originated in chill rooms that were set up by DJs off to the edge of club dance floors to give patrons a chance to take a break from the hectic dance vibe and chill out with this style of music.','Chill out (sometimes also chillout, chill-out, or simply chill), a term derived from a slang injunction to relax, emerged in the early and mid-1990s as a catch-all term for various styles of relatively mellow, slow-tempo music made by contemporary producers in the electronic music scene. The term &quot;Chill out music&quot;, as well as the genre itself, originated in chill rooms that were set up by DJs off to the edge of club dance floors to give patrons a chance to take a break from the hectic dance vibe and chill out with this style of music. Chill out as a musical genre or descriptive is synonymous with the more recently popularized terms &quot;smooth electronica&quot; and &quot;soft techno&quot; and is a loose genre of music blurring into several other very distinct styles of electronic and lo-fi music.	 	 Notable artists	 	 Although chill out is an emerging - however loose - genre of music, it is quite robust and features many prolific artists. Throughout the 1990s and the current decade, there have been many artists who have made a significant impact on what has come to be known as &quot;chill out music&quot; today. Among the most notable of those artists and projects are (in no order of precedence): Air, Fila Brazillia, Kruder &amp; Dorfmeister, dZihan &amp; Kamien, Thievery Corporation, Sven Van Hees, Lemongrass, Tosca, Ganga, Monte La Rue, Nightmares on Wax, The Dining Rooms, Bluetech, Sounds from the Ground, Jens Buchert, A Man Called Adam, Electric Skychurch, Mystical Sun, Single Cell Orchestra, Alex Cortiz, Zero 7, Sia, Boards of Canada, Stidiek. William Orbit, Groove Armada, Leftfield, Lenny Ibizarre, Timonkey, Banco de Gaia, Alan Steward and Lemon Jelly.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1054,'1054','10/08/2008','Downtempo (or Downbeat) is a laid-back electronic music style similar to ambient music, but usually with a beat or groove unlike the beatless forms of Ambient music. The beat is sometimes made from loops that have a hypnotic feeling. Sometimes the beats are more complicated and more featured instead of being in the background, but even then they are usually less intense than other kinds of electronic music like Trance.   ','Downtempo (or Downbeat) is a laid-back electronic music style similar to ambient music, but usually with a beat or groove unlike the beatless forms of Ambient music. The beat is sometimes made from loops that have a hypnotic feeling. Sometimes the beats are more complicated and more featured instead of being in the background, but even then they are usually less intense than other kinds of electronic music like Trance. 	 	 Often the name chill out music is used to refer to songs demonstrative of the genre, but those names also refer to other styles of music, and downtempo encompasses a wider variety of styles than those terms alone would indicate. 	 Another related genre is Trip hop, though Downtempo usually uses a slower tempo than Trip-hop. Due to the relaxing and often sensual or romantic feel of most downtempo music, along with the absence or minimal use of lyrics or vocals, it is a popular form of background music in %27chill out rooms%27 of dance parties, many alternative cafes, and is often marketed as being good music for lovemaking.	 	 ')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1057,'1057','20/03/2009','Electronica includes a wide range of contemporary electronic music designed for a wide range of uses, including foreground listening, some forms of dancing, and background music for other activities; but unlike electronic dance music, it is not specifically made for dancing. The term was first used in the United States in the early 1990s with regards to post-rave global-influenced electronic dance music.','Electronica includes a wide range of contemporary electronic music designed for a wide range of uses, including foreground listening, some forms of dancing, and background music for other activities; but unlike electronic dance music, it is not specifically made for dancing. The term was first used in the United States in the early 1990s with regards to post-rave global-influenced electronic dance music. Genres such as techno, drum and bass, downtempo, and ambient are among those encompassed by the umbrella term, entering the American mainstream from &quot;alternative&quot; or &quot;underground&quot; venues during the late 1990s. Prior to the adoption of electronica for this purpose, terms such as electronic listening music, trance and intelligent dance music (IDM) were used.	 	 The All Music Guide categorizes electronica as a top-level genre on their main page, where they state that electronica includes &quot;dozens of stylistic fusions&quot; ranging from danceable grooves to music for headphones and chillout areas.	 	 After beginning as an underground genre in the early 1990s, electronica has grown to influence even mainstream crossover recordings. Elements of electronica are used today by many popular artists in mainstream music.')

Despite only forming in March 2004, the band has gathered a surprisingly large fan base both in the UK and the U.S. Their debut EP, <em>This Is What The Edge Of Your Seat Was Made For</em>, came out in December 2004 and was the first release from the independent label Thirty Days Of Night Records. The band has since embarked on a number of UK tours supporting well-established bands such as Bleeding Through and Aiden, and also signed with Visible Noise Records in the autumn of 2005. The EP was re-released in January 2006 ,via Visible Noise, to a mainly positive critical response. In September 2006 the band won Best British Newcomer at the Kerrang!  Magazine Awards. Their debut album, <em>Count Your Blessings</em>, was released on 30th October 2006 amid a large headlining UK tour. As a very open and aggressive person the lead vocalist Oliver Sykes greatly encourages &quot;Wall of Death&quot; (or Braveheart) moshing, and has also asked for a &quot;Piggy-back Wall of Death&quot; during concerts and gigs. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1085,'1085','29/06/2009','Since their inception in 2004, the Riverside, CA quintet SUICIDE SILENCE have worked feverishly to carve out their own unique niche within the metal scene and in doing so they developed an undeniable buzz with legions of diehard supporters.  Their latest album <a title="Suicide Silence - No Time To Bleed" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Suicide+Silence/No+Time+To+Bleed" class="bbcode_album">No Time To Bleed</a>, was recorded with acclaimed producer Machine (Lamb Of God).  Suicide Silence started in late 2002 as a side project for its members who were all involved in other local bands at the time. Things didn’t get serious, however, until 2004, when the current lineup was solidified.','Since their inception in 2004, the Riverside, CA quintet SUICIDE SILENCE have worked feverishly to carve out their own unique niche within the metal scene and in doing so they developed an undeniable buzz with legions of diehard supporters.	 	 Their latest album <a title="Suicide Silence - No Time To Bleed" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Suicide+Silence/No+Time+To+Bleed" class="bbcode_album">No Time To Bleed</a>, was recorded with acclaimed producer Machine (Lamb Of God).	 	 Suicide Silence started in late 2002 as a side project for its members who were all involved in other local bands at the time. Things didn’t get serious, however, until 2004, when the current lineup was solidified. “Early on we were slower and sludgier,” explains drummer Josh Goddard, “but through a few member changes the sound became more powerful and energetic.” This mix of musicians brought together their influences—death metal, grindcore, black metal, hardcore, doom—and combined them into songs that are complex without being mystifying, and savagely fast and explosive without becoming a featureless blur.	 	 Their debut 5-song EP for Third Degree Records is a brutal testament to the sort of damage Suicide Silence is capable of inflicting. Though definitely rooted in what Goddard calls a “fast-paced death metal style,” it defies that genre’s sometimes predictable conventions, striving instead for something more unique. The songs are dynamic and crushing, shifting effortlessly from insane grind chaos into total molten sludge, with plenty of dynamic twists and turns along the way. Vocalist Mitch Lucker screams, growls and grunts over an ungodly guitar assault, while the band’s surgically precise rhythm section handles the disorienting time signatures and snail-paced grooves with equal efficiency.	 	 It is a sound that, though well-manifested on their EP, is devastating live. Suicide Silence’s breakdowns cause havoc in the pit, their blast-beats are neck-snapping and there is a palpable sense of barely controlled pandemonium when they play live. “We don’t hold back,” says Goddard, “and we try to give the crowd a show rather than standing around watching the moshpit and acting tough.” The reputation they’ve staked as a fearsome live act has brought them the opportunity to play with bands as diverse as God Forbid, Impaled, Bury Your Dead and Between the Buried and Me. And touring fervently in support of every release is a given.	 	 Suicide Silence may be a product of the burgeoning metal underground in the U.S., but their goals are far from modest. Without pandering to trends, or riding some scene’s coattails, the band always wants to move forward, wherever it takes them. “We never want to stop improving—as a band, as individual musicians, as songwriters and as performers,” says Goddard. “We want to make sure that every album we put out and every show we play is better than the last.”	    	User-contributed text is available under the Creative Commons By-SA License and may also be available under the GNU FDL.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1110,'1110','12/02/2010','Deathcore is an amalgamation of two musical styles: <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a>.   Deathcore is heavily influenced by modern <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a> in its speed, heaviness, and approach to chromatic, heavily palm muted riffing and dissonance. Traditional growls, and screaming are prevalent, and sometimes metalcore yelling or shouting vocals are included. Sometimes &quot;pig squeals&quot; are included. Much of deathcore features heavy, downtuned breakdowns and melodic riffs common in <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a>.','Deathcore is an amalgamation of two musical styles: <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a>. 	 	 Deathcore is heavily influenced by modern <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a> in its speed, heaviness, and approach to chromatic, heavily palm muted riffing and dissonance. Traditional growls, and screaming are prevalent, and sometimes metalcore yelling or shouting vocals are included. Sometimes &quot;pig squeals&quot; are included. Much of deathcore features heavy, downtuned breakdowns and melodic riffs common in <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a>. Deathcore brings in death metal influences in the forms of blast beats, low screams, and an altogether darker tone, while removing the metalcore tropes of dual harmonies and clean singing.	 	 Deathcore rose to popularity in the mid ’00s off the back of the American metalcore scene. Originally brought to the attention of the international metal media by bands from the southwestern scene such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Job+for+a+Cowboy" class="bbcode_artist">Job for a Cowboy</a> and Suicide Silence, it was immediately met with the same controversy as metalcore was, and the controversy continues to this day. However, nonetheless, it has been wildly successful, with many bands, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bring+Me+The+Horizon" class="bbcode_artist">Bring Me The Horizon</a> (now a pure metalcore band) gaining international renown, and has even influenced death metal bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Aborted" class="bbcode_artist">Aborted</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Cryptopsy" class="bbcode_artist">Cryptopsy</a>.')

Songs are high-tempo, short, with low-tuned guitars and blastbeats. The guitar style tends to have punkier scuzzy chord riffing than the cleaner, more technical and precise <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a>-grindcore/<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/deathgrind" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">deathgrind</a> fusion that came later. Grindcore can be see as having arisen from the same field of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/extreme%20hardcore%20punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">extreme hardcore punk</a> as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/crust" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">crust</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/thrashcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">thrashcore</a> that influenced metal genres such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/crossover%20thrash" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">crossover thrash</a> than being metal itself. It has all the characteristics of it%27s Emo and Punk roots, like a DIY ethic, and normally lo-fi production for example, but is more aggressive and chaotic than Emo, characterized with harsh, screamed vocals (duh) and experimental instrumentation. Some bands of this genre may employ odd tempo changes and other techniques, twinkly breakdowns, and generally have very fast paced and high-energy shows. The subject matter of Screamo is very broad, and more abstract, often with intelligent and poetic lyrics.','An off-shoot of Emotive Hardcore, or Emo for short, Screamo surfaced in the 90%27s, primarily. It has all the characteristics of it%27s Emo and Punk roots, like a DIY ethic, and normally lo-fi production for example, but is more aggressive and chaotic than Emo, characterized with harsh, screamed vocals (duh) and experimental instrumentation. Some bands of this genre may employ odd tempo changes and other techniques, twinkly breakdowns, and generally have very fast paced and high-energy shows. The subject matter of Screamo is very broad, and more abstract, often with intelligent and poetic lyrics. The Screamo scene is still alive today, especially in Europe.')

He was born in 1968.  	 2) <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Katerine+Avgoustakis" class="bbcode_artist">Katerine Avgoustakis</a> is a Belgian singer and was the winner of the 2005 Belgian Star Academy, similar to American Idol in the United States. ','There is more than one artist with this name:	 	 <strong>1)</strong> Philippe Katerine (known as <strong>Katerine</strong> for his artistic work) is a French singer and composer, who published eight records since the beginning of his career in 1991.	 He was born in 1968.	 	 	 <strong>2)</strong> <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Katerine+Avgoustakis" class="bbcode_artist">Katerine Avgoustakis</a> is a Belgian singer and was the winner of the 2005 Belgian Star Academy, similar to American Idol in the United States. She was born on September 16, 1983, to a Greek father and a Belgian mother.	 	 Currently, she lives in Maasmechelen. Avgoustakis used to be a beauty specialist and before that a saleswoman. During the third quarter of 2005, it was announced that Avgoustakis had been dating Pim Symoens, who was #4 in Star Academy and who also works for JIMtv, a popular Flemish music channel.	 	 Avgoustakis plays the piano and used to be in a choir. She was also a member of her first band Indiana, with whom she participated with for Eurovision Song Contest a couple of years ago, with the song Imitation Love.	 	 Due to the failure of Indiana, she entered Star Academy in Flanders. In 2005, she worked her way to the finale and won the contest and a record contract. Avgoustakis%27s debut single New Day, released in July 2005 in Belgium, peaked at #2 in the Belgian UltraTop 50 chart. &quot;New Day&quot; was written and produced by Regi Penxten &amp; Filip Vandueren, the team behind Milk Inc. Three months later, she received the TMF Flanders award for Best New National Artist for the song. Also the song was certified gold in Belgium. Her selfnamed debut album Katerine was released on November 14, 2005 in Belgium. The album is to be released in May in the Netherlands. Due the %27unexpected%27 sudden death of her mother, her second single, Here Come All the Boys, was delayed to be released in October 2005. This is the first single she also released in the Netherlands, that peaked at #89 in the Dutch Mega Singles Top 100. The song is also featured on the hits compilation HitBox, which was released on March 13, 2006, containing hits like Ricky Martin%27s I Don%27t Care, Rihanna%27s If It%27s Lovin%27 That You Want and the Michael Jackson cover Say Say Say (Waiting 4 U) by Hi_Tack.	 	 Avgoustakis won the first Belgian pre-selection for Eurosong 2006 on January 8, 2006 with the song Watch Me Move. Because of this, she was sure to have a place in the pre-finale rounds, however the judges thought her voice wasn%27t powerful enough to win. Despite being considered as one of the finalists, Katerine remained in the semi. 	 	 The third single from her album Katerine, Take Me Home, was released on April 4th 2006 in Belgium, with Watch Me Move as B-side.	 	 These days, Katerine is back with a new single called %27Livewire%27. Despite the high hopes, the single hasn%27t done as well as expected. The style is defined by the 808 and 808 drum samples arranged in syncopated rhythm patterns often resembling the Funk breaks used in Hip Hop  beats with simple, funky basslines. Other instrument parts are typically created with synthesizers and vocoder vocals are commonly used and delivered in a deadpan fashion to accentuate the robotic quality of the music.','Electro emerged with the development of early sampling technology and the introduction of the Roland TR-808 drum machine and is closely associated with Hip Hop%27s formative years in the early to mid 1980s. The style is defined by the 808 and 808 drum samples arranged in syncopated rhythm patterns often resembling the Funk breaks used in Hip Hop  beats with simple, funky basslines. Other instrument parts are typically created with synthesizers and vocoder vocals are commonly used and delivered in a deadpan fashion to accentuate the robotic quality of the music. While many of the definitive electro tracks are, in essence, also Hip Hop, in many instances it is simply electronic Funk and can also be considered an evolutionary link between the work of electronic groups in the 70s such as Kraftwerk and Techno  in the decade following. Electro%27s influence has long outlived its initial popularity with nearly every popular electronic dance genre at some point giving way to a hybridized electro subgenre. ')

Although closer in style to <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/grebo" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">grebo</a> the genre has connotations of being a %27new%27 version of %27rave%27, as well as being a corruption of the term %27new wave%27. Music publication NME is largely responsible for popularising the term throughout 2006 and 2007, despite itself claiming in mid-2008 reviews that &quot;New Rave is over&quot;. ','New Rave (sometimes labelled Nu Rave or Neu Rave), is a term applied to several types of music that go from fusing elements of new wave / disco / indie rock to techno / hip-house / breakbeat electro. Although closer in style to <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/grebo" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">grebo</a> the genre has connotations of being a %27new%27 version of %27rave%27, as well as being a corruption of the term %27new wave%27. Music publication NME is largely responsible for popularising the term throughout 2006 and 2007, despite itself claiming in mid-2008 reviews that &quot;New Rave is over&quot;.	 	 Klaxons, New Young Pony Club, Hadouken! and SHITDISCO are generally accepted as the main exponents of the genre.	 	 The aesthetics of the New Rave scene are as similar to those of Grebo as to the original rave scene, being mostly centred around psychedelic visual effects, while being much more fashion-conscious. Glowsticks, neon and other lights are common, and followers of the scene often dress in extremely bright and fluorescent colored clothing.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1451,'1451','02/09/2008','Música Popular Brasileira, or MPB, literally &quot;Brazilian Popular Music&quot;, designates a trend in post-Bossa Nova urban popular music. It is not a discrete genre but rather a constellation that combines original songwriting and updated versions of traditional Brazilian urban music styles like samba and samba-canção with contemporary influences, from folk to rock and pop. Signifying much more than the sum of the three words would indicate, &quot;MPB&quot; is a contemporary trend that has brought the world many renowned Brazilian artists.','Música Popular Brasileira, or MPB, literally &quot;Brazilian Popular Music&quot;, designates a trend in post-Bossa Nova urban popular music. It is not a discrete genre but rather a constellation that combines original songwriting and updated versions of traditional Brazilian urban music styles like samba and samba-canção with contemporary influences, from folk to rock and pop. Signifying much more than the sum of the three words would indicate, &quot;MPB&quot; is a contemporary trend that has brought the world many renowned Brazilian artists. The term can mean either any kind of music with Brazilian origins or a voice and guitar style that arose in the late 1960s.')

Originally the idea came from the requirement of the game called <a href="http://www.last.fm/group/Champion+of+Champions">Champion of Champions</a> that requires that you listen to music that has less than 2000 listeners. (If you are interested in playing such a game try <a href="http://www.last.fm/group/Obscure+Music+Game">Obscure Music Game</a> or <a href="http://www.last.fm/group/%5BGame%5D+Music+Knowledge+Challenge"> Music Knowledge Challenge</a>. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1457,'1457','15/09/2010','Funk is an American music genre that originated in the late 1960s when African American musicians blended soul music, soul jazz and R&amp;B into a rhythmic, danceable new form of music. Funk de-emphasizes melody and harmony and brings a strong rhythmic groove of electric bass and drums to the foreground. Funk songs are often based on an extended vamp on a single chord, distinguishing it from R&amp;B and soul songs centered around chord progressions.	 ','Funk is an American music genre that originated in the late 1960s when African American musicians blended soul music, soul jazz and R&amp;B into a rhythmic, danceable new form of music. Funk de-emphasizes melody and harmony and brings a strong rhythmic groove of electric bass and drums to the foreground. Funk songs are often based on an extended vamp on a single chord, distinguishing it from R&amp;B and soul songs centered around chord progressions.	 Like much African-inspired music, funk typically consists of a complex groove with rhythm instruments such as electric guitar, electric bass, Hammond organ, and drums playing interlocking rhythms. Funk bands sometimes have a horn section of several saxophones, trumpets, and in some cases, a trombone, which plays rhythmic &quot;hits&quot; or &quot;stabs&quot;.	 Many of the most famous bands in the genre also played disco and soul extensively. Funk music was a major influence on the development of disco music, and funk samples were present in most styles of house music and early hip hop music. It is also the main influence of go-go.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1591,'1591','20/09/2010','Noise music is one of several genres of music that feature nontraditional musical instruments. Noise music may incorporate, for example: manipulated recordings, static, feedback, live machine sound, circuit bent instruments, non-musical vocal elements, or any other noise source.  The genre is an avant-garde style that explores cacophony, repetitive sounds, atonal randomness, indeterminacy and dissonance to produce buildups and releases of emotional tension connected to the chthonic through dissonance and resolution.','Noise music is one of several genres of music that feature nontraditional musical instruments. Noise music may incorporate, for example: manipulated recordings, static, feedback, live machine sound, circuit bent instruments, non-musical vocal elements, or any other noise source.	 	 The genre is an avant-garde style that explores cacophony, repetitive sounds, atonal randomness, indeterminacy and dissonance to produce buildups and releases of emotional tension connected to the chthonic through dissonance and resolution. This emancipation of the dissonance was a concept put forth by Arnold Schoenberg (composer of atonal music and the inventor of the twelve tone technique) and others, including his pupil Anton Webern.	 	 The modern noise genre is largely a creation of Japanese noise musicians from the late 1970’s and early 1980’s.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1594,'1594','12/03/2010','Industrial music is a loose term for a number of different styles of experimental music, especially but not necessarily electronic music. The term was first used in the mid-1970s to describe the then-unique sound of Industrial Records artists. Since then, an extremely wide variety of labels and artists have since come to be called &quot;Industrial&quot;, however electropop, EBM, industrial rock etc should not be confused with this term.  ','Industrial music is a loose term for a number of different styles of experimental music, especially but not necessarily electronic music. The term was first used in the mid-1970s to describe the then-unique sound of Industrial Records artists. Since then, an extremely wide variety of labels and artists have since come to be called &quot;Industrial&quot;, however electropop, EBM, industrial rock etc should not be confused with this term.	 	 Originally, the term solely referred to music created by Industrial Records and related artists. As time progressed, the term began to refer to artists either directly influenced by the original movement, artists using an &quot;industrial&quot; aesthetic such as imagery devised around mechanical objects and industry itself and, more distantly, artists who were only minimally, often not at all, influenced or inspired by Industrial Records and related artists. The broadening of the term%27s musical definition has led to an overwhelming number of sub-genres and lines of influence.	 	 Industrial often, but not always, shares elements with the metal (&quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial metal</a>&quot;) and electronic (&quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/electro-industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">electro-industrial</a>&quot;, third wave post-industrial such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/powernoise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">powernoise</a> etc) genres.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1597,'1597','16/03/2009','Power Noise (also known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rhythmic%20noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rhythmic noise</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noize" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noize</a> and occasionally as distorted beat music) is a fusion genre between <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-industrial</a>  music and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/idm" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">idm</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/drum%20and%20bass" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">drum and bass</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hardcore%20techno" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hardcore techno</a>  or <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/breakcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">breakcore</a> , that takes its inspiration from some of the more structured and distorted early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> acts, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Esplendor+Geom%C3%A9trico" class="bbcode_artist">Esplendor Geom&eacute;trico</a>. The term &quot;Power Noise&quot; was originally coined by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Raoul+Roucka" class="bbcode_artist">Raoul Roucka</a>  of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex" class="bbcode_artist">Noisex</a>  in 1997...','Power Noise (also known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rhythmic%20noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rhythmic noise</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noize" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noize</a> and occasionally as distorted beat music) is a fusion genre between <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-industrial</a>  music and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/idm" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">idm</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/drum%20and%20bass" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">drum and bass</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hardcore%20techno" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hardcore techno</a>  or <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/breakcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">breakcore</a> , that takes its inspiration from some of the more structured and distorted early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> acts, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Esplendor+Geom%C3%A9trico" class="bbcode_artist">Esplendor Geom&eacute;trico</a>. The term &quot;Power Noise&quot; was originally coined by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Raoul+Roucka" class="bbcode_artist">Raoul Roucka</a>  of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex" class="bbcode_artist">Noisex</a>  in 1997, with the track <a title="Noisex &ndash; United (Power Noise Movement)" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex/_/United+%28Power+Noise+Movement%29" class="bbcode_track">United (Power Noise Movement)</a> and the genre was exposed to the US <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> Scene by the electro-industrial act <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%3Awumpscut%3A" class="bbcode_artist">:wumpscut:</a>, who signed <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex" class="bbcode_artist">Noisex</a> to the label Mental Ulcer Forges. Typically, Power Noise is based upon a distorted kick drum from a drum machine such as a Roland TR-909, uses militaristic 4/4 beats, and is usually instrumental. Sometimes a melodic component is added, but this is usually secondary to the rhythm. Power Noise tracks are typically structured and danceable, but are known to be occasionally abstract. This genre is showcased at the annual Maschinenfest festival in Krefeld, Germany, as well as at Infest in Bradford, UK.	 	 Bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Combichrist" class="bbcode_artist">Combichrist</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Dulce+Liquido" class="bbcode_artist">Dulce Liquido</a> partially belong to the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/aggrotech" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">aggrotech</a> genre as well, depending on albums and/or tracks..	 	 The term &quot;Power Noise&quot; should not be confused with the term &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/power%20electronics" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">power electronics</a>&quot;, which is a subgenre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noise</a>.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1600,'1600','30/09/2008','Power Noise (also known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rhythmic%20noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rhythmic noise</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noize" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noize</a> and occasionally as distorted beat music) is a fusion genre between <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-industrial</a>  music and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/idm" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">idm</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/drum%20and%20bass" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">drum and bass</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hardcore%20techno" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hardcore techno</a>  or <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/breakcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">breakcore</a> , that takes its inspiration from some of the more structured and distorted early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> acts, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Esplendor+Geom%C3%A9trico" class="bbcode_artist">Esplendor Geom&eacute;trico</a>. The term &quot;Power Noise&quot; was originally coined by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Raoul+Roucka" class="bbcode_artist">Raoul Roucka</a>  of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex" class="bbcode_artist">Noisex</a>  in 1997...','Power Noise (also known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rhythmic%20noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rhythmic noise</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noize" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noize</a> and occasionally as distorted beat music) is a fusion genre between <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-industrial</a>  music and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/idm" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">idm</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/drum%20and%20bass" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">drum and bass</a> , <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hardcore%20techno" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hardcore techno</a>  or <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/breakcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">breakcore</a> , that takes its inspiration from some of the more structured and distorted early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> acts, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Esplendor+Geom%C3%A9trico" class="bbcode_artist">Esplendor Geom&eacute;trico</a>. The term &quot;Power Noise&quot; was originally coined by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Raoul+Roucka" class="bbcode_artist">Raoul Roucka</a>  of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex" class="bbcode_artist">Noisex</a>  in 1997, with the track <a title="Noisex &ndash; United (Power Noise Movement)" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex/_/United+%28Power+Noise+Movement%29" class="bbcode_track">United (Power Noise Movement)</a> and the genre was exposed to the US <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> Scene by the electro-industrial act <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/%3Awumpscut%3A" class="bbcode_artist">:wumpscut:</a>, who signed <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Noisex" class="bbcode_artist">Noisex</a> to the label Mental Ulcer Forges. Typically, Power Noise is based upon a distorted kick drum from a drum machine such as a Roland TR-909, uses militaristic 4/4 beats, and is usually instrumental. Sometimes a melodic component is added, but this is usually secondary to the rhythm. Power Noise tracks are typically structured and danceable, but are known to be occasionally abstract. This genre is showcased at the annual Maschinenfest festival in Krefeld, Germany, as well as at Infest in Bradford, UK.	 	 Bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Combichrist" class="bbcode_artist">Combichrist</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Dulce+Liquido" class="bbcode_artist">Dulce Liquido</a> partially belong to the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/aggrotech" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">aggrotech</a> genre as well, depending on albums and/or tracks..	 	 The term &quot;Power Noise&quot; should not be confused with the term &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/power%20electronics" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">power electronics</a>&quot;, which is a subgenre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noise</a>.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1616,'1616','25/10/2009','Dark ambient is a subgenre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ambient" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ambient</a> music that features foreboding, ominous, or discordant overtones. Dark ambient emerged in the 1980s and 1990s with the introduction of new synthesizer and sampling technology in the electronic music genre and other technical advances in music. Dark ambient is a diverse genre, related to <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> music, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noise</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ethereal%20wave" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ethereal wave</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a>, yet generally free from derivatives and connections to other genres or styles.  ','Dark ambient is a subgenre of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ambient" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ambient</a> music that features foreboding, ominous, or discordant overtones. Dark ambient emerged in the 1980s and 1990s with the introduction of new synthesizer and sampling technology in the electronic music genre and other technical advances in music. Dark ambient is a diverse genre, related to <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> music, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">noise</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ethereal%20wave" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ethereal wave</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a>, yet generally free from derivatives and connections to other genres or styles.	 	 Dark ambient evolved partially based on several of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Brian+Eno" class="bbcode_artist">Brian Eno</a>%27s early collaborations that had a distinctly dark or discordant edge, notably &quot;An <a title="Brian Eno &ndash; Index of Metals" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Brian+Eno/_/Index+of+Metals" class="bbcode_track">Index of Metals</a>&quot; (from <a title="Brian Eno - Evening Star" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Brian+Eno/Evening+Star" class="bbcode_album">Evening Star</a> (1975)), a collaboration with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Robert+Fripp" class="bbcode_artist">Robert Fripp</a> that incorporated harsh guitar feedback, the ambient pieces on the second half of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/David+Bowie" class="bbcode_artist">David Bowie</a>%27s <a title="David Bowie - Low" href="http://www.last.fm/music/David+Bowie/Low" class="bbcode_album">Low</a>(1977), and Fourth World, Vol. 1: Possible Musics (1980), a collaboration with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Jon+Hassell" class="bbcode_artist">Jon Hassell</a>.	 	 Ambient industrial projects like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Coil" class="bbcode_artist">Coil</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Lilith" class="bbcode_artist">Lilith</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Lustmord" class="bbcode_artist">Lustmord</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Zoviet+France" class="bbcode_artist">Zoviet France</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Nocturnal+Emissions" class="bbcode_artist">Nocturnal Emissions</a> evolved out of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> music during the 1980s, and were some of the earliest artists to create consistently Dark Ambient music. In the late 1980s and early 1990s, an <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ethereal%20wave" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ethereal wave</a> trend emerged within the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/dark%20wave" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">dark wave</a> movement, that tended toward moody atmospheric pieces rather than jangly minor-<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/key%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">key rock</a>. <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ethereal%20wave" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ethereal wave</a> was mainly associated with the Projekt record label, with bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Black+Tape+for+a+Blue+Girl" class="bbcode_artist">Black Tape for a Blue Girl</a> doing music that ranged into moody ambient soundscapes.	 	 By the mid-1990s, a large number of artists were working in <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ambient%20industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ambient industrial</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ambient%20noise" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ambient noise</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ethereal%20wave" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ethereal wave</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/illbient" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">illbient</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/isolationism" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">isolationism</a>, and other emerging Dark Ambient styles. Among these artists were <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Autopsia" class="bbcode_')

Where <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> music was largely defined by the group <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Throbbing+Gristle" class="bbcode_artist">Throbbing Gristle</a> and the Industrial Records label, a considerable strain of Post-Industrial arguably begins with the post-<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Throbbing+Gristle" class="bbcode_artist">Throbbing Gristle</a> project <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Psychic+TV" class="bbcode_artist">Psychic TV</a> in the early 1980s...','Post-Industrial is a term used to refer to a grouping of music genres which developed in the 1980s, and which are related to the original usage of the term <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> music by Industrial Records through either influence or direct involvement, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/power%20electronics" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">power electronics</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death industrial</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/neofolk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">neofolk</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/martial%20industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">martial industrial</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/dark%20ambient" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">dark ambient</a>, and types of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/experimental" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">experimental</a> music. Where <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial</a> music was largely defined by the group <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Throbbing+Gristle" class="bbcode_artist">Throbbing Gristle</a> and the Industrial Records label, a considerable strain of Post-Industrial arguably begins with the post-<a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Throbbing+Gristle" class="bbcode_artist">Throbbing Gristle</a> project <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Psychic+TV" class="bbcode_artist">Psychic TV</a> in the early 1980s, and ideas hatched at that time. A number of key Post-Industrial music projects directly spun off early <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Psychic+TV" class="bbcode_artist">Psychic TV</a>, or were closely connected or influenced, by <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Psychic+TV" class="bbcode_artist">Psychic TV</a> and/or by its associated religious network Thee Temple ov Psychick Youth.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1690,'1690','27/11/2010','Chesney Henry &quot;Chet&quot; Baker Jr. (December 23, 1929 - May 13, 1988) was born in Yale, Oklahoma. A <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/trumpet" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">trumpet</a> player, Baker was an important part of the West coast &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/cool%20jazz" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">cool jazz</a>&quot; school of the 1950s. He first came to prominence in the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/jazz" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">jazz</a> world as part of the pianoless <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Gerry+Mulligan+Quartet" class="bbcode_artist">Gerry Mulligan Quartet</a> -- Mulligan had played with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Miles+Davis" class="bbcode_artist">Miles Davis</a>, whose <a title="Miles Davis - Birth of the Cool" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Miles+Davis/Birth+of+the+Cool" class="bbcode_album">Birth of the Cool</a> is recognized as ushering in the movement.    Baker%27s trumpet playing is characterized by incredibly sweet tones, clear and almost vibrato-less.','<strong>Chesney Henry &quot;Chet&quot; Baker Jr.</strong> (December 23, 1929 - May 13, 1988) was born in Yale, Oklahoma. A <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/trumpet" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">trumpet</a> player, Baker was an important part of the West coast &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/cool%20jazz" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">cool jazz</a>&quot; school of the 1950s. He first came to prominence in the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/jazz" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">jazz</a> world as part of the pianoless <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Gerry+Mulligan+Quartet" class="bbcode_artist">Gerry Mulligan Quartet</a> -- Mulligan had played with <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Miles+Davis" class="bbcode_artist">Miles Davis</a>, whose <em><a title="Miles Davis - Birth of the Cool" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Miles+Davis/Birth+of+the+Cool" class="bbcode_album">Birth of the Cool</a></em> is recognized as ushering in the movement.  	 	 Baker%27s trumpet playing is characterized by incredibly sweet tones, clear and almost vibrato-less. He was also a <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/vocal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">vocal</a>ist, and his vocal stylings matched his trumpet-playing in terms of style and feeling, with an emphasis on clarity and gentleness of expression, rather than vibrato or vocal pyrotechnics.	 	 While he was widely acclaimed musically, and his movie-star good looks ensured plenty of popular attention, his personal life was extremely troubled. A heroin addict, his relationships and life were marked by disorder. His addiction led to jail time, and a street fight with drug dealers caused him the loss of his front and other teeth, which forced him to learn to play the trumpet with dentures.	 	 For the last ten years of his life, Baker lived in Europe, where he toured and recorded extensively. Even though he was sunk in obscurity by the time, jazz afficionados consider his late recordings his best.	 	 He died in 1988 after falling from a window in the Prins Hendrick hotel in Amsterdam,  Holland. A plaque recognizing him is attached to the hotel. What would become Baker%27s last ever performance was held a few days earlier in the jazzbar Dizzy in Rotterdam.	 	 The life and times of Chet Baker were the subject of the Academy Award-nominated documentary <em>Let%27s Get Lost</em>, which was filmed and released the year of his death. A fictionalized mystery novel called <em>Looking for Chet Baker</em> by Bill Moody was published in 2002. 	    	User-contributed text is available under the Creative Commons By-SA License and may also be available under the GNU FDL.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1715,'1715','30/03/2010','Jazz is a musical art form which originated around the beginning of the 20th century in Black communities in the Southern United States from a confluence of African and European music traditions. The style%27s West African pedigree is evident in its use of blue notes, call-and-response, improvisation, polyrhythms, syncopation, and the swung note of ragtime.  From its early development until the present, jazz has also incorporated music from 19th and 20th century American popular music, which is based on European music traditions.','Jazz is a musical art form which originated around the beginning of the 20th century in Black communities in the Southern United States from a confluence of African and European music traditions. The style%27s West African pedigree is evident in its use of blue notes, call-and-response, improvisation, polyrhythms, syncopation, and the swung note of ragtime.	 	 From its early development until the present, jazz has also incorporated music from 19th and 20th century American popular music, which is based on European music traditions. The word jazz began as a West Coast slang term of uncertain derivation and was first used to refer to music in Chicago in about 1915.	 	 Jazz has, from its early 20th century inception, spawned a variety of subgenres, from New Orleans Dixieland dating from the early 1910s, big band-style swing from the 1930s and 1940s, bebop from the mid-1940s, a variety of Latin-jazz fusions such as Afro-Cuban and Brazilian jazz from the 1950s and 1960s, jazz-rock fusion from the 1970s and later developments such as acid jazz.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1721,'1721','17/08/2010','Cool jazz is a <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/jazz" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">jazz</a> style that emerged in the late 1940s in New York City.  During 1945, after the Second World War, there was an influx of Californian (predominantly white) jazz musicians to New York. Once there, these musicians mixed with the mostly black bebop musicians, but were also strongly influenced by the &quot;smooth&quot; sound of saxophonist <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Lester+Young" class="bbcode_artist">Lester Young</a>. The style that emerged became known as &quot;cool jazz&quot;, which avoided the aggressive tempos and harmonic abstraction of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/bebop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">bebop</a>. Cool jazz is often differentiated from other jazz idioms by its emphasis on the intellectual aspects of the music.','<strong>Cool jazz</strong> is a <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/jazz" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">jazz</a> style that emerged in the late 1940s in New York City.	 	 During 1945, after the Second World War, there was an influx of Californian (predominantly white) jazz musicians to New York. Once there, these musicians mixed with the mostly black bebop musicians, but were also strongly influenced by the &quot;smooth&quot; sound of saxophonist <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Lester+Young" class="bbcode_artist">Lester Young</a>. The style that emerged became known as &quot;cool jazz&quot;, which avoided the aggressive tempos and harmonic abstraction of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/bebop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">bebop</a>. Cool jazz is often differentiated from other jazz idioms by its emphasis on the intellectual aspects of the music. Such aspects would include intricate arrangements, innovative forms, and through composed feel (even through improvised sections.)	 	 Cool jazz had several sources and tributaries. Arrangers <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Gil+Evans" class="bbcode_artist">Gil Evans</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Gerry+Mulligan" class="bbcode_artist">Gerry Mulligan</a> developed their initial ideas working for the <span title="Unknown artist" class="bbcode_unknown">Michael Tower Orchestra</span>, which featured such then-unheard-of instruments (for jazz) as french horn and tuba; the added forces permitted Evans and Mulligan to explore softer emotional and timbral shading than had been typical of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/swing" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">swing</a>-era <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/big%20band" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">big band</a>s. Another variety of &quot;cool jazz&quot; was that of the pianist <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Lennie+Tristano" class="bbcode_artist">Lennie Tristano</a> and his students, notably the saxophonists <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Lee+Konitz" class="bbcode_artist">Lee Konitz</a> (who spent some time in the <span title="Unknown artist" class="bbcode_unknown">Thornhill band</span>) and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Warne+Marsh" class="bbcode_artist">Warne Marsh</a>. Tristano%27s music is very different from what Evans and his colleagues were up to: its &quot;coolness&quot; was a matter of emotional temperature (Tristano required saxophonists to play with a &quot;pure&quot; tone and to concentrate on melodic development and interaction rather than overt emotionalism), but his emphasis on sometimes ferociously fast tempos and on pure improvisation rather than arrangement was closer to bebop.	 	 The classic confluence of these various streams came with the 1949-1950 sessions now best known under their later title: <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Miles+Davis" class="bbcode_artist">Miles Davis</a>%27s <a title="Miles Davis - Birth of the Cool" href="http://www.last.fm/music/Miles+Davis/Birth+of+the+Cool" class="bbcode_album">Birth of the Cool</a> (1957). Despite Davis%27s top billing, this was in fact a collective project that drew together many players and arrangers/composers from the period: Davis, Evans, Mulligan, Konitz, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/John+Lewis" class="bbcode_artist">John Lewis</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Gunther+Schuller" class="bbcode_artist">Gunther Schuller</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Johnny+Carisi" class="bbcode_artist">Johnny Carisi</a>. Although Miles Davis was the musician who Gil Evans felt strongly to best represent this style of Jazz. Issued only shortly after bebop had begun to establish itself, it offered an alternative aesthetic that was initially unpopular – the recordings originally sold poorly and the band did not last long – but slowly established itself as a jazz classic.	 	 Despite its impact in the New York scene, cool jazz later became strongly identified with the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/west%20coast%20jazz" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">west coast jaz')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1727,'1727','09/04/2010','Blues is a vocal and instrumental form of music based on the use of &quot;blue notes.&quot; It emerged in Black communities of the United States from spirituals, work songs, field hollers, shouts and chants, and rhymed simple narrative ballads. The use of blue notes and the prominence of call-and-response patterns in the music and lyrics are indicative of African influence.   &quot;Blue notes,&quot; also known as &quot;worried notes,&quot; are the typically flattened third, fifth, and seventh degrees in a major scale. This is what gives the blues its inherent minor tonality.','Blues is a vocal and instrumental form of music based on the use of &quot;blue notes.&quot; It emerged in Black communities of the United States from spirituals, work songs, field hollers, shouts and chants, and rhymed simple narrative ballads. The use of blue notes and the prominence of call-and-response patterns in the music and lyrics are indicative of African influence. 	 	 &quot;Blue notes,&quot; also known as &quot;worried notes,&quot; are the typically flattened third, fifth, and seventh degrees in a major scale. This is what gives the blues its inherent minor tonality. From performer to performer, or from blues genre to genre, e.g., country blues, the deviation of the &quot;blue note&quot; from the actual scale can be greater.	 	 The blues influenced much of later American and Western popular music. It became one of the roots of jazz, rhythm and blues, and bluegrass. During the 1960s and 1970s, a hybrid form of the blues, blues rock, developed by combining of blues with various rock and roll forms.')

Specifically, this term is used when referring to popular music; some musical genres make little use of the human voice, such as jazz, electronic music, and large amounts of European classical music (although in electronic music the voice can be sampled just like anything else). In commercial music, some tracks or songs on a compact disc include instrumental tracks. These tracks are often exact copies of the corresponding song, but do not have vocals. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1862,'1862','05/04/2010','Rooted in garage rock and other forms of what is now known as protopunk music, punk rock bands eschewed the perceived excesses of mainstream 1970s rock. They created fast, hard-edged music, typically with short songs, stripped-down instrumentation, and often political, anti-establishment lyrics. Punk embraces a DIY (do it yourself) ethic, with many bands self-producing their recordings and distributing them through informal channels.','Rooted in garage rock and other forms of what is now known as protopunk music, punk rock bands eschewed the perceived excesses of mainstream 1970s rock. They created fast, hard-edged music, typically with short songs, stripped-down instrumentation, and often political, anti-establishment lyrics. Punk embraces a DIY (do it yourself) ethic, with many bands self-producing their recordings and distributing them through informal channels. The ideals associated with punk music have caused a rift between fans of the music due to mainstream bands claiming the title while not applying any of the characteristics aside from instrumental simplicity.	 	 However before the UK %2782 and US Hardcore styles emerged, and with them certain &quot;uniforms&quot; and unifying culture, punk was less of an aesthetically homogenous style and more of an umbrella movement where uniqueness and self-expression were encouraged. Examples of this are the original New York punk bands associated with CBGBs who had very little in common stylistically, and also the bands involved in the UK scene who used elements of reggae or goth in their music (in fact it was from this post-punk scene that goth eventually emerged). Therefore it is arguable that any band rooted in punk yet creating their own sound against expectations are more in the spirit of true punk than a band sticking rigidly to the genre blueprints. ')

Several members have several masks that are interchanged during any one time period, most notably Chris (#3) and Sid (#0). INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1943,'1943','27/01/2011','Heavy metal (often referred to simply as metal) is a genre of rock music that developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s, largely in the United Kingdom and the United States. With roots in blues-rock and psychedelic rock, the bands that created heavy metal developed a thick, massive sound, characterized by highly amplified distortion, extended guitar solos, emphatic beats, and overall loudness. Heavy metal lyrics and performance styles are generally associated with masculinity and machismo.  ','Heavy metal (often referred to simply as metal) is a genre of rock music that developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s, largely in the United Kingdom and the United States. With roots in blues-rock and psychedelic rock, the bands that created heavy metal developed a thick, massive sound, characterized by highly amplified distortion, extended guitar solos, emphatic beats, and overall loudness. Heavy metal lyrics and performance styles are generally associated with masculinity and machismo.	 	 The first heavy metal bands such as Led Zeppelin, Black Sabbath and Deep Purple attracted large audiences, though they were often critically reviled, a status common throughout the history of the genre. In the mid-1970s Judas Priest helped spur the genre’s evolution by discarding much of its blues influence; Motörhead introduced a punk rock sensibility and an increasing emphasis on speed. Bands in the New Wave of British Heavy Metal such as Iron Maiden followed in a similar vein. Before the end of the decade, heavy metal had attracted a worldwide following of fans known as “metalheads” or “headbangers”.	 	 In the 1980s, glam metal became a major commercial force with groups like Mötley Crüe. Underground scenes produced an array of more extreme, aggressive styles: thrash metal broke into the mainstream with bands such as Metallica, while other styles like death metal and black metal remain subcultural phenomena. Since the mid-1990s, popular styles such as nu metal, which often incorporates elements of grunge and hip hop; and metalcore, which blends extreme metal with hardcore punk, have further expanded the definition of the genre. ')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1946,'1946','25/08/2010','Nu metal, also spelled nu-metal,  was primarily a collection of bands that mixed various other genres with heavy rock music, including but not limited to hip-hop, industrial and funk. The earlier bands, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Korn" class="bbcode_artist">Korn</a> were inspired by artists such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Faith+No+More" class="bbcode_artist">Faith No More</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Primus" class="bbcode_artist">Primus</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Helmet" class="bbcode_artist">Helmet</a>, and genres such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/funk%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">funk metal</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rapcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rapcore</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial rock</a>. In its usual form, it takes rhythmic elements from hip-hop/industrial metal and distorted guitars from metal/post-hardcore, combined with clean or screamed/shouted vocals, (rap is also sometimes used but not as often).','Nu metal, also spelled nu-metal,  was primarily a collection of bands that mixed various other genres with heavy rock music, including but not limited to hip-hop, industrial and funk. The earlier bands, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Korn" class="bbcode_artist">Korn</a> were inspired by artists such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Faith+No+More" class="bbcode_artist">Faith No More</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Primus" class="bbcode_artist">Primus</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Helmet" class="bbcode_artist">Helmet</a>, and genres such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/funk%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">funk metal</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rapcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rapcore</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial rock</a>. In its usual form, it takes rhythmic elements from hip-hop/industrial metal and distorted guitars from metal/post-hardcore, combined with clean or screamed/shouted vocals, (rap is also sometimes used but not as often). Nu metal also sometimes employs turntables.	 	 	 The technique that nu metal guitarists use is detuned strings whose lower pitch creates a thicker, more resonant sound. Strings detuned in this way are often drop-D or lower, sometimes adding a seventh string. When the band <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/+noredirect/Ko%D0%AFn" class="bbcode_artist">Ko?n</a> first began its career, members of the band stated that guitar solos had become saturated and too boring in the music industry, thus they felt no need for them.	 	 Nu metal%27s orgins are in the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/90s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">90s</a> in Southern California, from bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Deftones" class="bbcode_artist">Deftones</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/+noredirect/Ko%D0%AFn" class="bbcode_artist">Ko?n</a>. Other main artists are <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Disturbed" class="bbcode_artist">Disturbed</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Mudvayne" class="bbcode_artist">Mudvayne</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Godsmack" class="bbcode_artist">Godsmack</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Drowning+Pool" class="bbcode_artist">Drowning Pool</a>.	 	 Nu metal is controversial among the fans of more established metal genres, who often consider the hip hop influence negative, as well as the mainstream popularity of several bands. A very commonly held opinion by traditional metal musicians, like Zakk Wylde, was that nu metal bands did not do solos primarily because of their inabilities to execute complex and intricate scales. This is typical of nu metal bands in that guitar solos are rare in nu metal songs in general.	 	 History	 	 In Nu-metal: The Next Generation of Rock &amp; Punk, Joel McIver cites the bands Faith No More, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Beastie Boys, Nirvana and Jane%27s Addiction as setting up various musical characteristics which are prominent in the genre.Producer Ross Robinson has also been cited as a key figure in shaping the genre.	 	 In 1994, Korn became the first band to be labeled as &quot;nu metal&quot;.	 	 The genre, which became popular in the 90%27s and early 2000%27s, demonstrated that &quot;pancultural metal could pay off.Nu metal gained mainstream success through MTV and Ozzy Osbourne%27s 1996 introduction of Ozzfest, which led the media to talk of a resurgence of heavy metal.	 	 The resurgence led to heavy metal gaining popularity amongst a much younger audience.While nu metal was widely popular, traditional metal fans did not fully embrace the style.	 	 2000-2006: Commercial success	 	 In the early 2000s, artists and bands including Pantera, Rob Zombie, Marilyn Manson, Mudvayne, Slipknot, Incubus, Linkin Park,System of a Down, and Disturbed played the yearly music festival.Two compilation albums of the Ozzfest tour were released, one covering select 2001 performances and another for 2002.	 	 On-stage foot')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1949,'1949','10/02/2011','Rock music is a genre of music started in America. It has its roots in 1940s and 1950s rock and roll and rockabilly, which evolved from blues, country music and other influences. According to the All Music Guide, “In its purest form, Rock &amp; Roll has three chords, a strong, insistent back beat, and a catchy melody.  Early rock &amp; roll drew from a variety of sources, primarily blues, R&amp;B, and country, but also gospel, traditional pop, jazz, and folk. All of these influences combined in a simple, blues-based song structure that was fast, danceable, and catchy.','Rock music is a genre of music started in America. It has its roots in 1940s and 1950s rock and roll and rockabilly, which evolved from blues, country music and other influences. According to the All Music Guide, “In its purest form, Rock &amp; Roll has three chords, a strong, insistent back beat, and a catchy melody.  Early rock &amp; roll drew from a variety of sources, primarily blues, R&amp;B, and country, but also gospel, traditional pop, jazz, and folk. All of these influences combined in a simple, blues-based song structure that was fast, danceable, and catchy.” Rock usually has a prominent vocal melody, accompanied by guitar, drums, and bass. Many styles of rock music also use keyboard instruments such as organ, piano, mellotron, and synthesizers. Other instruments sometimes utilized in rock include saxophone (originally in the 50s the central instrument), harmonica, violin, flute, French horn, banjo, melodica, and timpani. Also, less common stringed instruments such as mandolin and sitar are used. Rock music usually has a strong back beat, and often revolves around the guitar, either solid electric, hollow electric, or acoustic.	 	 In the late 1960s, rock music was blended with folk music to create folk rock, blues to create blues-rock and with jazz, to create jazz-rock fusion, and without a time signature to create psychedelic rock. In the 1970s, rock incorporated influences from soul, funk, and latin music. Also in the 1970s, rock developed a number of subgenres, such as soft rock, heavy metal, hard rock, progressive rock, and punk rock. Rock subgenres that emerged in the 1980s included synthpop, hardcore punk and alternative rock. In the 1990s, rock subgenres included grunge, Britpop, indie rock, and nu metal.	 	 A group of musicians specializing in rock music is called a rock band or rock group. Many rock groups consist of a guitarist, lead singer, bass guitarist, and drummer, forming a quartet. Some groups omit one or more of these roles and/or utilize a lead singer who plays an instrument while singing, forming a trio or duo; others include additional musicians such as one or two rhythm guitarists and/or a keyboardist. More rarely, groups also utilize stringed instruments such as violins or cellos, and/or horns like saxophones, trumpets or trombones.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(1997,'1997','17/08/2007','faca is an <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/electro" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">electro</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/surf" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">surf</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/big%20beat" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">big beat</a>, a go-go, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/lo-fi" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">lo-fi</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/electroclash" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">electroclash</a> band from Barijuana (Bariloche), Argentina and Tijuana, Mexico. The band members are Facundo Delgado and Valeria Leyva, they claim to make fun-playful and innocent commercial surf for all the continent. They met online and they produce their music and change their material via msn.	 ----------------o-------------------  Faca es un trío formado por dos personas.','faca is an <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/electro" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">electro</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/surf" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">surf</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/big%20beat" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">big beat</a>, a go-go, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/lo-fi" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">lo-fi</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/electroclash" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">electroclash</a> band from Barijuana (Bariloche), Argentina and Tijuana, Mexico. The band members are Facundo Delgado and Valeria Leyva, they claim to make fun-playful and innocent commercial surf for all the continent. They met online and they produce their music and change their material via msn.	 ----------------o-------------------	 	 Faca es un trío formado por dos personas. Una orquesta electro-repleta de confetti, fiesta, alegría y baile, aunque por definición, es un instrumento de arma blanca que usan en las prisiones en Argentina, también significa el sobrenombre de uno de los dos integrantes del grupo.	 	 El dúo está conformado por Facundo Delgado (oriundo de Bariloche, Argentina) quien es el encargado de la parte compositiva de los collages de sonidos y por Valeria Leyva (Tijuana, Mexico - San Diego, USA) quien es la principal voz, cara, espíritu y alma viva del grupo.	 	 A pesar que Valeria y Facundo hasta la fecha no se conocen personalmente (sólo se conocen vía Internet) han logrado trabajar a la distancia como un equipo y consolidar este proyecto dejando como resultado un producto artístico lleno de aires de optimismo y diversión. Ellos comprueban que no es necesario que dos personas se encuentren en la misma habitación para trabajar en conjunto, sino que, gracias a la tecnología, no existen fronteras ni barreras que los limiten, el único límite es la imaginación.	 	 Los shows en vivo corren por cuenta de Valeria, quien se encarga de las voces y tracks en PC, a veces respaldada por músicos amigos quienes tocan guitarra, bajo, etc.	 	 Principalmente enfocado en los estilos <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/surf" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">surf</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/big%20beat" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">big beat</a>, a go-go, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/lo-fi" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">lo-fi</a> y <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/electroclash" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">electroclash</a>, el dúo de música cybernética trata de demostrar que con espontaneidad y originalidad se puede lograr algo visual y auditivamente agradable. Usando las herramientas más básicas y una visión por lograr algo nuevo y natural han creado música y arte en &quot;baja calidad con alta tecnología&quot;, y todo esto, al servicio de la diversión.	 	 Tablas de surf, discotheques, bikinis, glamour, lo-fi electro-pop y mucha adrenalina. Algo así como Dick Dale con 18 años, techno, lentes Ray Ban y una notebook bajo el brazo.	 	 	  	    	User-contributed text is available under the Creative Commons By-SA License and may also be available under the GNU FDL.')

','<strong>Queens of the Stone Age</strong> is a <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hard%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hard rock</a> band from Palm Desert, California, United States. QOTSA formed in 1997, rising from the ashes of Kyuss and began playing together during the now legendary <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Desert+Sessions" class="bbcode_artist">Desert Sessions</a>. Homme has drawn all of the members from that diverse group of musicians for QOTSA. The band originally formed under the name <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Gamma+Ray" class="bbcode_artist">Gamma Ray</a>, but almost faced a lawsuit from the European <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metal</a> band of the same name.
