INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(5679,'5679','15/12/2009','Emo is a style of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock</a> music typically characterized by melodic musicianship and expressive, often confessional lyrics. It originated in the mid-<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/1980s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">1980s</a> <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hardcore%20punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hardcore punk</a> movement of Washington, D.C., where it was known as &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/emotional%20hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">emotional hardcore</a>&quot; or &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/emocore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">emocore</a>&quot; and pioneered by bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Rites+of+Spring" class="bbcode_artist">Rites of Spring</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Embrace" class="bbcode_artist">Embrace</a>. As the style was echoed by contemporary American punk bands, its sound and meaning shifted and changed, blending with <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop%20punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop punk</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/indie%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">indie rock</a> and encapsulated in the early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/1990s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">1990s</a> by groups such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Jawbreaker" class="bbcode_artist">Jawbreaker</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Sunny+Day+Real+Estate" class="bbcode_artist">Sunny Day Real Estate</a>.','Emo is a style of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock</a> music typically characterized by melodic musicianship and expressive, often confessional lyrics. It originated in the mid-<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/1980s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">1980s</a> <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hardcore%20punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hardcore punk</a> movement of Washington, D.C., where it was known as &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/emotional%20hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">emotional hardcore</a>&quot; or &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/emocore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">emocore</a>&quot; and pioneered by bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Rites+of+Spring" class="bbcode_artist">Rites of Spring</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Embrace" class="bbcode_artist">Embrace</a>. As the style was echoed by contemporary American punk bands, its sound and meaning shifted and changed, blending with <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop%20punk" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop punk</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/indie%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">indie rock</a> and encapsulated in the early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/1990s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">1990s</a> by groups such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Jawbreaker" class="bbcode_artist">Jawbreaker</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Sunny+Day+Real+Estate" class="bbcode_artist">Sunny Day Real Estate</a>. By the mid 1990s numerous emo acts emerged from the Midwestern and Central United States, and several independent record labels began to specialize in the style.	 	 Emo broke into mainstream culture in the early <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/2000s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">2000s</a> with the platinum-selling success of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Jimmy+Eat+World" class="bbcode_artist">Jimmy Eat World</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Dashboard+Confessional" class="bbcode_artist">Dashboard Confessional</a> and the emergence of the more aggressive subgenre &quot;<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/screamo" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">screamo</a>&quot;. In recent years the term &quot;emo&quot; has been applied by critics and journalists to a variety of artists, including multiplatinum acts such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Fall+Out+Boy" class="bbcode_artist">Fall Out Boy</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/My+Chemical+Romance" class="bbcode_artist">My Chemical Romance</a> and disparate groups such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Coheed+and+Cambria" class="bbcode_artist">Coheed and Cambria</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/+noredirect/Panic+at+the+Disco" class="bbcode_artist">Panic at the Disco</a>.	 	 In addition to music, &quot;emo&quot; is often used more generally to signify a particular relationship between fans and artists, and to describe related aspects of fashion, culture, and behavior.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(5682,'5682','25/02/2011','An off-shoot of Emotive Hardcore, or Emo for short, Screamo surfaced in the 90%27s, primarily. It has all the characteristics of it%27s Emo and Punk roots, like a DIY ethic, and normally lo-fi production for example, but is more aggressive and chaotic than Emo, characterized with harsh, screamed vocals (duh) and experimental instrumentation. Some bands of this genre may employ odd tempo changes and other techniques, twinkly breakdowns, and generally have very fast paced and high-energy shows. The subject matter of Screamo is very broad, and more abstract, often with intelligent and poetic lyrics.','An off-shoot of Emotive Hardcore, or Emo for short, Screamo surfaced in the 90%27s, primarily. It has all the characteristics of it%27s Emo and Punk roots, like a DIY ethic, and normally lo-fi production for example, but is more aggressive and chaotic than Emo, characterized with harsh, screamed vocals (duh) and experimental instrumentation. Some bands of this genre may employ odd tempo changes and other techniques, twinkly breakdowns, and generally have very fast paced and high-energy shows. The subject matter of Screamo is very broad, and more abstract, often with intelligent and poetic lyrics. The Screamo scene is still alive today, especially in Europe.')

','Fuad:	 Fuad has been playing music since the days of %27Alvin and the Chipmunks%27 …a junior high school death metal band was the start of Fuad’s on-stage rock gigs. Born into a typical &quot;cultural&quot; Bangladeshi family, Fuad started performing on stage from the age of 6. He plays bass, keyboards, drums, and rhythm guitar. A strong love for music and performance fused with a drive for success made Fuad take up music as a career. He is the music director at w4 records (west4 group), and has his own recording studio in NYC.	 Fuad%27s role in Zefyr is quite complicated. Zefyr made appearances in two mixed albums by west4 records in which Fuad was the vocalist, he also played bass, guitars, keyboards, and engineered the sessions. But live shows and studio recordings are so different, because he can%27t play his first instrument - drums - and simultaneously sing in the live shows. Therefore, Tuman was chosen to take over the vocal duties in the band.	 Fuad also performs with many renowned Bangladeshi artists such as Babey Nazneen, Tapan Chowdhury,Andrew Kishore, Kumar Bishwajit, Konok Chapa, Mumtaj Baul, Sabina Yasmin, Asif,Jewel, Shaqila Zafr, Shuvra Dev, Ayub Bachchu, Ankhi Alamgir, Rizia Parvin, Bappy Laheri and various others on their US tours.	 Fuad%27s gear: Pearl export kit, washburn bass -- alder body with blue top, maple neck, 2 WB950 humbucking pickups, rosewood fingerboard, WB510 active tone control preamp w/ pan pot, 20 frets. Richard:	 The founding member of Zefyr, Richard has been strumming and tapping his guitar since the days of ripped jeans, white hi-top sneakers and Metallica t-shirts. Fortunately, as time passed, Richard%27s clothing improved as did his playing. His style ranges from eastern folk/traditional to western blues rock.	 Richard%27s best attribute is his ability to create ingeniously sly solos on the spot. His fingers flow naturally, hitting just the right notes to create beautiful masterpieces. His worst quality is his inability to remember those beautiful solos for the next session :)	 Richard performs with many illustrious Bangladeshi artists, such as Manna Dey, Babey Nazneen, Tapan Chowdhury,Andrew Kishore, Kumar Bishwajit, Konok Chapa and many others.	 Richard loves the attacking sound of Ibanez guitars, he plays a custom made Ibanez S1520FB model - Two Quantum series humbuckers; special 5 wiring and a Lo-Pro edge tremolo.	 	 Paul:	 A band called DHRUBO (early 90%27s - Bangladesh) was the start for Paul%27s music career. Paul joined Zefyr in 1999, after a few Jam sessions at Roxy studios, it was clear that Paul was the missing link. He has a way of bringing all the instruments together with his vibrant style. In his stage persona he has a brooding, lifeless pose but if you listen you can hear the great %27Silent Thunder%27! :)	 Paul is heavily into classic rock, 80%27s metal, alternative rock, grunge and soft rock. Paul%27s biggest influences include STP, OZZY, MEGADETH, and Pink Floyd.	 Paul uses Warwick Corvette Classic bass, Fender Jazz Bass, Crate stacks and heads, Digitech and Zoom processors. Paul%27s playing ranges from funk-rock to soft-rock, to hip-hop, to metal.	 	 Tuman:	 Tuman%27s flirtation with music started at a young age when he first discovered classic rock and screamed along with the rebellious lyrics. His yells soon turned to song and he%27s been singing on Brooklyn rooftops since. He has been an on and off member of Zefyr since 1997 but only recently decided to focus his vocal talents wholeheartedly on the band. His electrifying stage persona gives Zefyr an adrenaline boost on top of their caffeinated-sugar-high in live performances.	 His diverse musical taste ranges from Gipsy &amp; Baul to Classical, over Jazz, Electonica, Roots Rock Reggae &amp; Funk among a laundry list of other genres.	 Among other things, ')

Unfortunately the lead snagged on a snake, so he had to go back in the swamp to plug it back in. Once that was successfully accomplished, he was able to consistently pour molten liquid jive from the earth into the stratosphere at rates seldom seen before, during or since. 	 	 This jive, what did we do with it?	 	 If you could be king for a day...	 	 ...Why don%27t you just fuck off?	 	 Bulot%27s ever-beyond magico-crypto-deca-soundsphere-hedrons remind us of everything that man lost when he gained speech. All that is implied by the Zizeckian %27tragic imprint of the human voice%27 is here, in waves of undulating tone that fizz like a seltzer in water, that are as still as a crocodile tempting a fish. We%27ve lost so much, he says, without words, without gestures. 	 	 He%27s back in the swamp now, the mud too thick for his tones to get out to us. But we had him there, for some time. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(5812,'5812','27/03/2010','The term experimental music refers to the creative process that the artist goes through to create a variety of unique sounds that when mixed together create a whole new experience in music. The process of &quot;experimentation&quot; is just as important as the outcome. &quot;Experimental&quot; music could be called more of an experience as it is not made to be distributed in the main stream but rather to give you an insight of the artists%27 complex minds.  ','The term <strong>experimental</strong> music refers to the creative process that the artist goes through to create a variety of unique sounds that when mixed together create a whole new experience in music. The process of &quot;experimentation&quot; is just as important as the outcome. &quot;Experimental&quot; music could be called more of an experience as it is not made to be distributed in the main stream but rather to give you an insight of the artists%27 complex minds.	 	 &quot;Experimental&quot; implies a profound level of inventiveness that lies completely outside the traditions of music.  It is not bound by any established rules or formulas.  Many times, the outcome of the composers%27 creative efforts is unpredictable as the composer &quot;experiments&quot; with various processes and novel approaches to produce sound or contrive a listening experience.  	 	 These experiments many times give rise to new genres of music such as: industrial, noise, free jazz, electronica, tape music, noise rock, etc.  Once those genres become more established, formulaic and recycled, they no longer strictly fit the definition of experimental music.  They may become decidedly unexperimental as norms within the genre solidify.  In order to keep experimental experimental, the composer(s) must continuously discard tradition (even tradition established by other experimental composers) and create the unexpected, reimagined, and possibly, the socially unacceptable.	 	 Experimental music refers, in the English-language literature, to a compositional tradition which arose in the mid-twentieth century, applied particularly in North America to music composed in such a way that its outcome is unforeseeable. Its most famous and influential exponent was <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/John+Cage" class="bbcode_artist">John Cage</a> (Grant 2003, 174). More loosely, the term &quot;experimental&quot; is used in conjunction with genre names to describe music within specific genres that pushes against their boundaries or definitions, or else whose approach is a hybrid of disparate styles, or incorporates unorthodox, new, distinctly unique ingredients (Anon. [n.d.]a). Similarly, it has sometimes been used to describe &quot;transethnic&quot; music: the mixture of recognizable music genres. A quite distinct sense was current in the late 1950s to describe computer-controlled composition, and the term at that time also was sometimes used for electronic music and musique concrète. &quot;Experimental music&quot; has also been used in music journalism as a general term of disapprobation for music departing from traditional norms.')

For example, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock%20and%20roll" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock and roll</a> originally developed as a fusion of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/blues" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">blues</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/gospel" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">gospel</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/country" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">country</a> music. The main characteristics of fusion genres are variations in tempo, rhythm and sometimes the use of long musical &quot;journeys&quot; that can be divided into smaller parts, each with their own dynamics, style and tempo.','A fusion genre is a music genre which combines two or more genres, although it usually is used to refer to <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/jazz%20fusion" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">jazz fusion</a>. For example, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock%20and%20roll" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock and roll</a> originally developed as a fusion of <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/blues" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">blues</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/gospel" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">gospel</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/country" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">country</a> music. The main characteristics of fusion genres are variations in tempo, rhythm and sometimes the use of long musical &quot;journeys&quot; that can be divided into smaller parts, each with their own dynamics, style and tempo.')

Lenorman was born at the Château de Bénouville, Calvados (Normandy) when it was a maternity hospital. He is the son of Madeleine Lenormand and an unknown German soldier. Lenorman has four children: Mathieu, Justine, Clémence and Victor. He released his first album in 1968.  In 1988 he represented France in the Eurovision Song Contest in Dublin, Ireland, reaching tenth place with Chanteur de charme. Lenorman was very popular in France and Francophonie, during the 1970s and early 1980s.','Gérard Lenorman (born 9 February 1945) is a French singer.	 	 Lenorman was born at the Château de Bénouville, Calvados (Normandy) when it was a maternity hospital. He is the son of Madeleine Lenormand and an unknown German soldier. Lenorman has four children: Mathieu, Justine, Clémence and Victor. He released his first album in 1968.	 	 In 1988 he represented France in the Eurovision Song Contest in Dublin, Ireland, reaching tenth place with Chanteur de charme. Lenorman was very popular in France and Francophonie, during the 1970s and early 1980s. In 1994, a compilation of his hits went gold in France. In 2007, he released a biography entitled Je suis né à vingt ans (&quot;I was born at the age of 20&quot;) in which the singer explains the unknown identity of his father. The genre includes both <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/instrumental" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">instrumental</a> forms (often played on light of tone instruments such as the <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/hammond%20organ" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">hammond organ</a>, &quot;lush strings&quot;, or <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/ukulele" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">ukulele</a>); and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/vocal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">vocal</a> forms featuring <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop%20singers" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop singers</a>, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Barbra+Streisand" class="bbcode_artist">Barbra Streisand</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Perry+Como" class="bbcode_artist">Perry Como</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Andy+Williams" class="bbcode_artist">Andy Williams</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Jack+Jones" class="bbcode_artist">Jack Jones</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Engelbert+Humperdinck" class="bbcode_artist">Engelbert Humperdinck</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Eydie+Gorme" class="bbcode_artist">Eydie Gorme</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Barry+Manilow" class="bbcode_artist">Barry Manilow</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/+noredirect/Harry+Connick+Jr." class="bbcode_artist">Harry Connick Jr.</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Frank+Sinatra" class="bbcode_artist">Frank Sinatra</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Johnny+Mathis" class="bbcode_artist">Johnny Mathis</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bing+Crosby" class="bbcode_artist">Bing Crosby</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Tom+Jones" class="bbcode_artist">Tom Jones</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Mel+Torm%C3%A9" class="bbcode_artist">Mel Torm&eacute;</a>. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(5872,'5872','27/08/2009','Paul Personne (de son vrai nom René-Paul Roux) est un guitariste et chanteur français de blues et de rock né à Argenteuil le 27 décembre 1949.	 Paul grandit donc en région parisienne, et suit l’influence mélomane de son père qui joue de temps en temps de l’harmonica. Mais c’est surtout en écoutant la radio que Paul Personne va se forger sa propre culture musicale, qui englobe aussi bien Piaf que Johnny Hallyday ou encore Eddy Mitchell. Paul commence l’apprentissage de la musique en faisant de la batterie et de la guitare, et évolue dans plusieurs groupes à l’adolescence. ','Paul Personne (de son vrai nom René-Paul Roux) est un guitariste et chanteur français de blues et de rock né à Argenteuil le 27 décembre 1949.	 Paul grandit donc en région parisienne, et suit l’influence mélomane de son père qui joue de temps en temps de l’harmonica. Mais c’est surtout en écoutant la radio que Paul Personne va se forger sa propre culture musicale, qui englobe aussi bien Piaf que Johnny Hallyday ou encore Eddy Mitchell. Paul commence l’apprentissage de la musique en faisant de la batterie et de la guitare, et évolue dans plusieurs groupes à l’adolescence.	 	 C’est avec le groupe L’Origine que Paul va enregistrer son premier titre sur le label Pathé Marconi. Mais L’Origine n’arrivera pas à percer et Paul doit se trouver un boulot (agro)alimentaire pour vivre. La musique fait sa réapparition dans l’existence de Paul lorsque ce dernier fait la connaissance du Liquid Theater, une troupe de théâtre avec qui il fonde le collectif La Folle Entreprise. Mais ce nouveau groupe ne réussira pas non plus à enregistrer plus d’un titre. Par conséquent, Paul doit une fois de plus renoncer à ses projets artistiques et le musicien part vivre à Toulouse avec femme et enfant. Mais la guitare lui fait les yeux doux constamment, et Paul finit par craquer : il crée un autre groupe, Bracos Band, avec qui il écume les salles de concert ainsi que les festivals. Et comme de bien entendu, la nouvelle formation enregistre un titre en 1977 pour se séparer ensuite. Mais Paul ne désespère pas et forme encore un groupe, Backstage, composé simplement d’un batteur, d’un bassiste, et de Paul himself. Et là, miracle, le groupe signe d’abord chez Vogue, puis publie deux albums, entre 1979 et 1980. Seulement, Backstage ne s’entend plus avec sa maison de disques, et le groupe finit par splitter…Comme d’habitude…	 	 Les échecs successifs de Paul amènent ce dernier à se poser des questions : peut-être devrait-il arrêter d’écrire en anglais, même si ça sonne mieux sur du blues, peut-être qu’une carrière solo serait moins casse-gueule que la vie de groupe…Paul change alors de langue au début des années 1980 et publie un premier album solo en 1982 sous le nom de Paul Personne. On commence à entendre parler du musicien, mais le label CBS chez qui il a signé, le vire avant que Paul sorte un deuxième opus.	 	 Décidément, l’industrie du disque a une dent contre Personne, ou peut-être que ce dernier tend un peu trop à se plier aux exigences des labels, et l’authenticité de sa musique alors en pâtit. Paul finit par trouver LA solution miracle à ses problèmes musicaux : 1) créer des mélodies sincères et spontanées à son image 2) arrêter de corrompre ses sons et son propre rythme au nom du business 3) s’obstiner à offrir une musique hors normes et habitée. Et quand Paul Personne sort l’album « Exclusif » en 1983, il est enfin quelqu’un, parce qu’il a su rester lui-même en présentant au public des perles blues sublimes et intenses. Le disque cartonne au tête des charts, notamment grâce aux hits « Ça va rouler » et « Comme un étranger ».	 	 Fort de ce succès inespéré, Paul remet le couvert en 1984 avec un nouvel opus, « Barjoland », et un an plus tard, récidive avec « 24/24». Entre temps, Paul a perdu sa fille, et le bluesman a du mal à surmonter sa peine. Pendant quelques temps, Paul reste à l’écart du milieu musical, préférant rester en famille. En 1987, il fait cependant son grand retour sur scène au Québec, et deux ans après, sort « La Chance », un opus inspiré qui séduit de nouveau les aficionados de blues. En 1991, sort l’album live « La Route de la chance », mais le musicien a vraiment la poisse puisque sa maison de disques fait faillite…Paul Personne signe donc un nouveau contrat avec Polydor et publie « Comme à la maison » en 1992. L’année 1993 sera quant à elle riche en évènements, puisque Paul participe à l’album « Rio Grande » d’Eddy Mitchell, et joue au Parc des Princes aux côtés de Johnny Hallyday à l’occasion de son grand concert organisé pour ses')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(5882,'5882','21/08/2008','Blues-rock is a hybrid musical genre combining bluesy improvisations over the 12-bar blues and extended boogie jams with Rock and roll styles. The core of the blues rock sound is created by the electric guitar, bass guitar and drum kit, with the electric guitar usually amplified through a tube guitar amplifier, giving it an overdriven character.  The style began to develop in the mid-1960s in England and the United States, as what one music critic called a &quot;genre of rhythm%27n%27blues played by white European musicians&quot;.','Blues-rock is a hybrid musical genre combining bluesy improvisations over the 12-bar blues and extended boogie jams with Rock and roll styles. The core of the blues rock sound is created by the electric guitar, bass guitar and drum kit, with the electric guitar usually amplified through a tube guitar amplifier, giving it an overdriven character.	 	 The style began to develop in the mid-1960s in England and the United States, as what one music critic called a &quot;genre of rhythm%27n%27blues played by white European musicians&quot;. UK Bands such as The Animals, Cream and The Rolling Stones experimented with music from the older American bluesmen like Howlin%27 Wolf, Jimmy Reed and Muddy Waters. While the early blues-rock bands &quot;attempted to play long, involved improvisations which were commonplace on jazz records&quot;, by the 1970s, blues rock got heavier and more riff-based. By the &quot;early %2770s, the lines between blues-rock and hard rock were barely visible&quot;, as bands began recording rock-style albums. In the 1980s and 1990s, blues-rock bands returned to their bluesy roots, and some of these bands, such as the &quot;Fabulous Thunderbirds and Stevie Ray Vaughan flirted with rock stardom.&quot;	 	 Blues-rock can be characterized by bluesy improvisation, the 12-bar blues, extended boogie jams typically focused on the electric guitar player, and often a heavier, riff-oriented sound and feel to the songs than might be found in traditional Chicago-style blues. Blues rock bands &quot;borrow[ed] the idea of an instrumental combo and loud amplification from rock &amp; roll&quot;. It is also often played at a fast tempo, again distinguishing it from the blues.	 	 The core of the blues rock sound is created by the electric guitar, bass guitar and drum kit. The electric guitar is usually amplified through a tube guitar amplifier or using an overdrive effect. Often two guitars are played in blues rock bands, one playing the accompaniment riffs and chords on rhythm guitar and one playing the melodic lines and solos of the lead guitar part. While 1950s-era blues bands would sometimes still use the upright bass, the blues rock bands of the 1960s used the electric bass, which was easier to amplify to loud volumes. Keyboard instruments such as the piano and Hammond organ are also occasionally used. As with the electric guitar, the sound of the Hammond organ is typically amplified with a tube amplifier, which gives a growling, &quot;overdriven&quot; sound quality to the instrument. Vocals also typically play a key role, although the vocals may be equal in importance or even subordinate to the lead guitar playing; as well, a number of blues-rock pieces are instrumental-only.	 	 ')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(5885,'5885','09/04/2010','Blues is a vocal and instrumental form of music based on the use of &quot;blue notes.&quot; It emerged in Black communities of the United States from spirituals, work songs, field hollers, shouts and chants, and rhymed simple narrative ballads. The use of blue notes and the prominence of call-and-response patterns in the music and lyrics are indicative of African influence.   &quot;Blue notes,&quot; also known as &quot;worried notes,&quot; are the typically flattened third, fifth, and seventh degrees in a major scale. This is what gives the blues its inherent minor tonality.','Blues is a vocal and instrumental form of music based on the use of &quot;blue notes.&quot; It emerged in Black communities of the United States from spirituals, work songs, field hollers, shouts and chants, and rhymed simple narrative ballads. The use of blue notes and the prominence of call-and-response patterns in the music and lyrics are indicative of African influence. 	 	 &quot;Blue notes,&quot; also known as &quot;worried notes,&quot; are the typically flattened third, fifth, and seventh degrees in a major scale. This is what gives the blues its inherent minor tonality. From performer to performer, or from blues genre to genre, e.g., country blues, the deviation of the &quot;blue note&quot; from the actual scale can be greater.	 	 The blues influenced much of later American and Western popular music. It became one of the roots of jazz, rhythm and blues, and bluegrass. During the 1960s and 1970s, a hybrid form of the blues, blues rock, developed by combining of blues with various rock and roll forms.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(5989,'5989','25/10/2009','Emo violence is foremost a combination of screamo and power violence. From power violence it has taken the fast part and the hardcore part, from emo the screamy vocals (no barking as in pv then) and more varied pallete of emotions – not just pissed off anger. Genre defining bands were <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/In%252FHumanity" class="bbcode_artist">In/Humanity</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Palatka" class="bbcode_artist">Palatka</a>. Usage of this tag is debatable, however, as the term originated in a joke told by members of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/In%252FHumanity" class="bbcode_artist">In/Humanity</a>, and there is very little to separate emo violence from screamo at large. screamo has always incorporated fast, thrashy songwriting.','Emo violence is foremost a combination of screamo and power violence. From power violence it has taken the fast part and the hardcore part, from emo the screamy vocals (no barking as in pv then) and more varied pallete of emotions – not just pissed off anger. Genre defining bands were <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/In%252FHumanity" class="bbcode_artist">In/Humanity</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Palatka" class="bbcode_artist">Palatka</a>. Usage of this tag is debatable, however, as the term originated in a joke told by members of <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/In%252FHumanity" class="bbcode_artist">In/Humanity</a>, and there is very little to separate emo violence from screamo at large. screamo has always incorporated fast, thrashy songwriting. Some screamo artists have emphasized this thrashy, powerviolence-esque part of their sound more than others, yet it is unclear where the line is between a heavy screamo band and an emo-violence band. The detabe about the usefulness or legitimacy of this label thus continues...')

This later evolved in the mid <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/90s" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">90s</a>, when bands began to take cues from <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic death metal</a> bands like <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/At+the+Gates" class="bbcode_artist">At the Gates</a>, while still retaining their hardcore punk attitude and stance. Early examples of Metalcore, or what some might consider <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metallic%20hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metallic hardcore</a> include <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Integrity" class="bbcode_artist">Integrity</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Earth+Crisis" class="bbcode_artist">Earth Crisis</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Disembodied" class="bbcode_artist">Disembodied</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Converge" class="bbcode_artist">Converge</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Overcast" class="bbcode_artist">Overcast</a>. Early examples of Metalcore, or what some might consider <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metallic%20hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metallic hardcore</a> include <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Integrity" class="bbcode_artist">Integrity</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Earth+Crisis" class="bbcode_artist">Earth Crisis</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Disembodied" class="bbcode_artist">Disembodied</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Converge" class="bbcode_artist">Converge</a>, and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Overcast" class="bbcode_artist">Overcast</a>. 	 	 Metalcore itself has its own offshoots and derivatives such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic death metal</a> infused <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/melodic%20metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">melodic metalcore</a>, technical <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/mathcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">mathcore</a>, and the fusion of metalcore with death metal known as <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/deathcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">deathcore</a> which has become a huge trend in recent years . There are also a number of bands who mix Metalcore influences with <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/groove%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">groove metal</a>; taking cues from <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Pantera" class="bbcode_artist">Pantera</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/black%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">black metal</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/post-hardcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">post-hardcore</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/progressive%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">progressive metal</a>, or even classic <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/heavy%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">heavy metal</a> influences in some cases. 	 	 More recent and commercially successful bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Killswitch+Engage" class="bbcode_artist">Killswitch Engage</a>, <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Trivium" class="bbcode_artist">Trivium</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bullet+for+My+Valentine" class="bbcode_artist">Bullet for My Valentine</a> tend to stray more towards metal or even pop rock, with cleaner, more melodic vocals and guitar. This may have been a factor in the classification of Metalcore as a mainstream trend. With %27<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">rock</a>%27 and %27<a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/pop%20rock" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">pop rock</a>%27 fans being attracted to the more mainstream sound, rather than the heavy, fast riffs and screaming vocals of past bands. 	 	 Metalcore has gained a very big following, but also had its fair share of critics on both the punk and metal sides of the spectrum. INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6092,'6092','12/02/2010','Deathcore is an amalgamation of two musical styles: <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a>.   Deathcore is heavily influenced by modern <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a> in its speed, heaviness, and approach to chromatic, heavily palm muted riffing and dissonance. Traditional growls, and screaming are prevalent, and sometimes metalcore yelling or shouting vocals are included. Sometimes &quot;pig squeals&quot; are included. Much of deathcore features heavy, downtuned breakdowns and melodic riffs common in <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a>.','Deathcore is an amalgamation of two musical styles: <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a>. 	 	 Deathcore is heavily influenced by modern <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">death metal</a> in its speed, heaviness, and approach to chromatic, heavily palm muted riffing and dissonance. Traditional growls, and screaming are prevalent, and sometimes metalcore yelling or shouting vocals are included. Sometimes &quot;pig squeals&quot; are included. Much of deathcore features heavy, downtuned breakdowns and melodic riffs common in <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/metalcore" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">metalcore</a>. Deathcore brings in death metal influences in the forms of blast beats, low screams, and an altogether darker tone, while removing the metalcore tropes of dual harmonies and clean singing.	 	 Deathcore rose to popularity in the mid ’00s off the back of the American metalcore scene. Originally brought to the attention of the international metal media by bands from the southwestern scene such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Job+for+a+Cowboy" class="bbcode_artist">Job for a Cowboy</a> and Suicide Silence, it was immediately met with the same controversy as metalcore was, and the controversy continues to this day. However, nonetheless, it has been wildly successful, with many bands, such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Bring+Me+The+Horizon" class="bbcode_artist">Bring Me The Horizon</a> (now a pure metalcore band) gaining international renown, and has even influenced death metal bands such as <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Aborted" class="bbcode_artist">Aborted</a> and <a href="http://www.last.fm/music/Cryptopsy" class="bbcode_artist">Cryptopsy</a>.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6165,'6165','17/03/2009','The accordion is a portable box-shaped musical instrument of the hand-held bellows-driven free-reed aerophone family, sometimes referred to as a squeezebox. A person who plays the accordion is called an accordionist. It is played by compressing or expanding a bellows, while pressing buttons or keys, causing valves called pallets to open which allow air to flow across strips of brass or steel called reeds that vibrate to produce sound inside the body.  ','The accordion is a portable box-shaped musical instrument of the hand-held bellows-driven free-reed aerophone family, sometimes referred to as a squeezebox. A person who plays the accordion is called an accordionist. It is played by compressing or expanding a bellows, while pressing buttons or keys, causing valves called pallets to open which allow air to flow across strips of brass or steel called reeds that vibrate to produce sound inside the body.	 	 The instrument is sometimes considered a &quot;one-man-band&quot;, as it needs no accompanying instrument; the performer normally plays the melody on buttons or keys on the right-hand manual, and the accompaniment—consisting of bass and pre-set chord buttons—on the left-hand manual.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6188,'6188','14/07/2009','Reggae as a class of music with its slow bass beat is a very enjoyable genre. It is hard not to give credit or turn away from the man who put this genre of music and his country on the map. Bob Marley%27s powerful political lyrics and new age sound has become timeless. It is more&quot; today&quot; then it was when he wrote it; timeless work, absolutely timeless. He also comes from humble beginnings in the St Anne township (the same township as the first lady of Jamaica).','Reggae as a class of music with its slow bass beat is a very enjoyable genre. It is hard not to give credit or turn away from the man who put this genre of music and his country on the map. Bob Marley%27s powerful political lyrics and new age sound has become timeless. It is more&quot; today&quot; then it was when he wrote it; timeless work, absolutely timeless. He also comes from humble beginnings in the St Anne township (the same township as the first lady of Jamaica). He never forgot how painful it was to be a black man even in a country that is predominately black, sharing with the people of his homeland that they had no voice, no freedom. They were slaves on the sugar plantations of wealthy foreign Colonialists. or on the plantations themselves.  He must have literally clawed his way to the top. Much has been said about his recreational use of Marijuana, as if this choice somehow negates his impact on his accomplishments. With ultimate human fragility and irony, his mind was destroyed by brain cancer which is what killed him. His son, Ziggy Marley is also a singer. They have very different sounds and lyrical content. Ziggy Marley is also a great talent in his own right. There are days when listening carefully to Bob Marley%27s music, one can be transported to to a church listening to the great Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. ; or take another journey to the crowed, dirty streets of India listening to the the gentle martyr, Papa Gandhi. These are all extraordinary voices of liberation. Bob Marley%27s message was no less important because his death did not come at the end of a gun. God bless him and the many others who have the courage not only to think great things but to share them. 	 	 But beyond Bob Marley, there is a whole world of other roots reggae artists. Producers such as Lee &quot;Scratch&quot; Perry, King Tubby, and Keith Hudson produced dubbed out tracks for many many bands. Bands to check out are Israel Vibration, The Upsetters, Augustus Pablo, Culture, and Sugar Minott. For more modern roots music, check out 10 ft. Ganja Plant or Giant Panda Guerilla Dub Squad. ')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6287,'6287','10/04/2010','IDM can refer both to Intelligent dance music (aka <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/braindance" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">braindance</a>) and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial death metal</a>. IDM is a popular name for an electronic music genre that emerged in the early 1990s at the end of the British rave era. The genre is influenced by a wide range of musical styles particularly electronic dance music such as Detroit Techno. Stylistically, IDM tends to rely upon individualistic experimentation rather than on a particular set of musical characteristics.','IDM can refer both to Intelligent dance music (aka <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/braindance" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">braindance</a>) and <a href="http://www.last.fm/tag/industrial%20death%20metal" class="bbcode_tag" rel="tag">industrial death metal</a>. IDM is a popular name for an electronic music genre that emerged in the early 1990s at the end of the British rave era. The genre is influenced by a wide range of musical styles particularly electronic dance music such as Detroit Techno. Stylistically, IDM tends to rely upon individualistic experimentation rather than on a particular set of musical characteristics. The range of post-techno styles to emerge in the early 1990s were described variously as art techno, ambient techno, intelligent techno, and electronica. In America the latter term is now used by the music industry as a catchall to describe EDM and its many derivatives.	 	 The term IDM is said to have originated in the United States in 1993 with the formation of the IDM list, an electronic mailing list originally charted for the discussion of music by (but not limited to) a number of prominent British artists, especially those appearing on a 1992 Warp Records compilation called Artificial Intelligence. The term is still seen by some as being peculiar to the U.S. but it is routinely used by music journalists, record labels, and fans on both sides of the Atlantic.')

The style is defined by the 808 and 808 drum samples arranged in syncopated rhythm patterns often resembling the Funk breaks used in Hip Hop  beats with simple, funky basslines. Other instrument parts are typically created with synthesizers and vocoder vocals are commonly used and delivered in a deadpan fashion to accentuate the robotic quality of the music.','Electro emerged with the development of early sampling technology and the introduction of the Roland TR-808 drum machine and is closely associated with Hip Hop%27s formative years in the early to mid 1980s. The style is defined by the 808 and 808 drum samples arranged in syncopated rhythm patterns often resembling the Funk breaks used in Hip Hop  beats with simple, funky basslines. Other instrument parts are typically created with synthesizers and vocoder vocals are commonly used and delivered in a deadpan fashion to accentuate the robotic quality of the music. While many of the definitive electro tracks are, in essence, also Hip Hop, in many instances it is simply electronic Funk and can also be considered an evolutionary link between the work of electronic groups in the 70s such as Kraftwerk and Techno  in the decade following. Electro%27s influence has long outlived its initial popularity with nearly every popular electronic dance genre at some point giving way to a hybridized electro subgenre. ')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6293,'6293','01/05/2010','Breakbeat (sometimes breakbeats or breaks) is a term used to describe a collection of sub-genres of electronic music, usually characterized by the use of a non-straightened 4/4 drum pattern (as opposed to the steady beat of house or trance). These rhythms may be characterised by their intensive use of syncopation and polyrhythms.  History  In the late 1970s and early 1980s, hip-hop DJs (starting with Kool DJ Herc) began using several breaks (the part of a funk or jazz song in which the music &quot;breaks&quot;...','Breakbeat (sometimes breakbeats or breaks) is a term used to describe a collection of sub-genres of electronic music, usually characterized by the use of a non-straightened 4/4 drum pattern (as opposed to the steady beat of house or trance). These rhythms may be characterised by their intensive use of syncopation and polyrhythms.	 	 History	 	 In the late 1970s and early 1980s, hip-hop DJs (starting with Kool DJ Herc) began using several breaks (the part of a funk or jazz song in which the music &quot;breaks&quot; to let the rhythm section play unaccompanied) in a row to use as the rhythmic basis for hip-hop songs. Kool DJ Herc%27s breakbeat style was to play the same record on two turntables and play the break repeatedly by alternating between the two records (letting one play while spinning the second record back to the beginning of the break). This style was copied and improved upon by early hip hop DJs Afrika Bambaataa and Grand Wizard Theodore.[1] This style was extremely popular in clubs and dance halls because the extended breakbeat was the perfect backdrop for breakdancers to show their skills.	 	 The Amen Break, a drum break from The Winston%27s song &quot;Amen, Brother&quot; is widely regarded as the most used break ever. This break was first used on &quot;King of the Beats&quot; by Mantronix, and has since been used in thousands of songs. Other popular breaks are from James Brown%27s &quot;Funky Drummer&quot; and &quot;Give it Up or Turnit a Loose&quot;, The Incredible Bongo Band%27s &quot;Apache&quot;, and Lyn Collins%27 &quot;Think (About It)&quot;.[1]	 	 In the early 1990s, acid house artists and producers started using breakbeat samples in their music to create breakbeat hardcore, also known as rave music. The hardcore scene then diverged into sub-genres like jungle and drum and bass, which generally had a darker sound and focused more on complex sampled drum patterns. A good example of this is Goldie%27s album %27Timeless%27.	 	 In 1992 a new style called &quot;jungalistic hardcore&quot; emerged, and for many ravers it was too funky to dance to. Josh Lawford of Ravescene prophesied that the breakbeat was &quot;the death-knell of rave&quot; [2] because the ever changing drumbeat patterns of breakbeat music didn%27t allow for the same zoned out, trance-like state that the standard, steady 4/4 beats of rave enabled.	 	 In recent times, the term breakbeat has become synonymous with the many genres of breaks music which have become popular within the global dance music scene, including big beat, nu skool breaks and progressive breaks. DJs from a variety of genres, including house and techno, work breaks tracks into their sets. This may occur because the tempo of breaks tracks (ranging from 110 to 150 beats per minute) means they can be readily mixed with these genres, whereas the comparatively fast speed of jungle and drum and bass (160-180 bpm) may have restricted the utility of these subgenres to DJs playing slower-tempo music.	 	 In the present day, breakbeats can be heard constantly in every day life. Breakbeats are used in many hip hop, rap, jungle, and hardcore songs, and can also be heard in other music, from popular music to background music in car and jean commercials on the radio or TV. [3]	 	 Sampled breakbeats	 	 With the advent of digital sampling and music editing on the computer, breakbeats have become much easier to create and use. Now, instead of cutting and splicing tape sections or constantly backspinning 2 records at the same time, a computer program can be used to cut, paste, and loop breakbeats endlessly. Digital effects like filters, reverb, reversing, time stretching, and pitch shifting can be added to the beat, and even to individual sounds by themselves. Individual instruments from within a breakbeat can be sampled one by one and combined with others, to build new breakbeat patterns from the ground up. The Prodigy, a popular group, uses digitally sampled and chopped breakbeats in many of')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6331,'6331','14/07/2010','Jean-Jacques Perrey (born January 20, 1929, France) is one of the unchallenged pioneers of electronic music. An avant-gardist with sense of daftness, his name resounded throughout the land since the track &quot;E.V.A.&quot; was remixed by Fatboy Slim. At the age of 76 he released a new album. Nowadays he is known as one of the creators of pop music.   Perrey was born in France in 1929. He was studying medicine in Paris when he met George Jenny, inventor of the Ondioline. Quitting medical school, Perrey travelled through Europe demonstrating this keyboard ancestor of the modern synthesizer.','Jean-Jacques Perrey (born January 20, 1929, France) is one of the unchallenged pioneers of electronic music. An avant-gardist with sense of daftness, his name resounded throughout the land since the track &quot;E.V.A.&quot; was remixed by Fatboy Slim. At the age of 76 he released a new album. Nowadays he is known as one of the creators of pop music. 	 	 Perrey was born in France in 1929. He was studying medicine in Paris when he met George Jenny, inventor of the Ondioline. Quitting medical school, Perrey travelled through Europe demonstrating this keyboard ancestor of the modern synthesizer. At the age of 30, Perrey relocated to New York, sponsored by Caroll Bratman, who built him an experimental laboratory and recording studio. Here he invented &quot;a new process for generating rhythms with sequences and loops&quot;, utilising the environmental sounds of &quot;musique concrète.&quot; With scissors, splicing tape, and tape recorders, he spent weeks piecing together a uniquely comique take on the future. Befriending Robert Moog, he became one of the first Moog synth musicians, creating &quot;far out electronic entertainment&quot;. In 1965 Perrey met Gershon Kingsley, a former colleague of John Cage. Together, using Ondioline and Perrey%27s loops, they created two albums for Vanguard — The In Sound From Way Out (1966) and Kaleidoscopic Vibrations (1967). Perrey and Kingsley collaborated on sound design for radio and television advertising. Perrey returned to France, composing for television, scoring for ballet and continuing medical research into therapeutic sounds for insomniacs.	 	 The rap group Beastie Boys released an instrumental CD titled, as a tribute to Perrey &amp; Kingsley, The In Sound From Way Out.	 	 Most recently, Perrey has been collaborating with Seattle music/composer Dana Countryman, and they have released two CDs on Oglio Records, &quot;The Happy Electropop Music Machine&quot;, and &quot;Destination Space&quot;.	 	 In 2010, his song &quot;Chicken on the Rocks&quot; was featured in an episode of &quot;South Park&quot;.	 	 	 His official website can be found at: <a href="http://www.jeanjacquesperrey.com/" rel="nofollow">http://www.jeanjacquesperrey.com/</a>	    	User-contributed text is available under the Creative Commons By-SA License and may also be available under the GNU FDL.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6349,'6349','22/11/2008','Space age pop is a general and loosely based term for a music genre associated with certain Mexican and American composers and songwriters in the Space Age of the 1950s and 1960s. It is also called bachelor pad music or lounge music. Space age pop was inspired by the zeitgeist of those times, an optimism based on the strong post-war economy and technology boom, and excitement about mankind%27s early forrays into space.','Space age pop is a general and loosely based term for a music genre associated with certain Mexican and American composers and songwriters in the Space Age of the 1950s and 1960s. It is also called bachelor pad music or lounge music. Space age pop was inspired by the zeitgeist of those times, an optimism based on the strong post-war economy and technology boom, and excitement about mankind%27s early forrays into space. Although there is no specific album, date, or year when the genre was born, producer Irwin Chusid identifies its heyday as &quot;roughly 1954 to 1964—from the dawn of high-fidelity (hi-fi) to the arrival of the Beatles.&quot;	 	 The music is not limited to a single style, and it is not always easily categorized. There are several styles that can be recognized as an influence: classical composers like Ravel and Debussy; the big bands of the 1940s; and different exotic styles, such as samba, latin, and calypso jazz. Space Age pop is related to the genres of lounge music, exotica, or beautiful music and may be regarded as a precursor to the musical genre of space music.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6383,'6383','09/03/2011','Vladimir Cosma was born April 13, 1940 in Bucarest, Romania, into a family of musicians.  After receiving first prizes for violin and composition at the Bucarest Conservatoire of Music, he arrived in Paris in 1963 and continued his studies at the Conservatoire National Supérieur de Musique de Paris, working with Nadia Boulanger. As well as for classical music he discovered early on a passion for jazz, film music and all forms of popular music.  ','Vladimir Cosma was born April 13, 1940 in Bucarest, Romania, into a family of musicians.	 	 After receiving first prizes for violin and composition at the Bucarest Conservatoire of Music, he arrived in Paris in 1963 and continued his studies at the Conservatoire National Supérieur de Musique de Paris, working with Nadia Boulanger. As well as for classical music he discovered early on a passion for jazz, film music and all forms of popular music.	 	 From 1964 he made a number of international tours as a concert violinist and began to devote himself more and more to composing. He wrote various compositions including: &quot;Trois mouvements d’été&quot; for symphony orchestra, &quot;Oblique&quot; for violoncello and string orchestra, music for theatre and ballet (&quot;Volpone&quot; for the Comédie Française, the opera &quot;Fantômas&quot;…).	 	 In 1968, Yves Robert entrusted him with his first film music for &quot;Alexandre le Bienheureux&quot;.	 	 Vladimir Cosma has since composed more than three hundred scores for feature films and TV series.	 	 He is dedicated to re-writing his film music with the intention of conducting performances in symphonic concerts, thus approaching a wider audience than at the cinema.	 	 Vladimir Cosma received two Césars for the best movie score, for &quot;Diva&quot; (1982) and &quot;Le Bal&quot; (1984), two Golden Sevens for the best music for television, as well as a number of prizes and awards in France and other countries.	 	 He has also obtained numerous gold and platinum records all over the world (France, Germany, Japan, England, Switzerland, Belgium, Italy, Holland, Scandinavia…)	 	 Vladimir Cosma is Chevalier de l%27ordre National la Légion d’Honneur, Grand Officier du Mérite Culturel Roumain, as well as Commandeur des Arts et des Lettres.	    	User-contributed text is available under the Creative Commons By-SA License and may also be available under the GNU FDL.')

INSERT INTO WIKI(cle_primaire, id_wiki, datePublication, resume, contenu)values(6401,'6401','26/07/2010','The double bass, also called the string bass, upright bass, bass violin or contrabass, is the largest and lowest-pitched bowed string instrument in the modern symphony orchestra. The double bass is a standard member of the string section of the symphony orchestra[1] and smaller string ensembles[2] in Western classical music. In addition, it is used in other genres such as jazz, 1950s-style blues and rock and roll, rockabilly/psychobilly, traditional country music, bluegrass, tango and many types of folk music.	 ','The double bass, also called the string bass, upright bass, bass violin or contrabass, is the largest and lowest-pitched bowed string instrument in the modern symphony orchestra. The double bass is a standard member of the string section of the symphony orchestra[1] and smaller string ensembles[2] in Western classical music. In addition, it is used in other genres such as jazz, 1950s-style blues and rock and roll, rockabilly/psychobilly, traditional country music, bluegrass, tango and many types of folk music.	 The double bass is typically constructed from several types of wood, including maple for the back, spruce for the top, and ebony for the fingerboard. It is uncertain whether the instrument is a descendant of the viola da gamba or of the violin, but it is traditionally aligned with the violin family. While the double bass is nearly identical in construction to other violin family instruments, it also embodies features found in the older viol family.	 Like many other string instruments, the double bass is played either with a bow (arco) or by plucking the strings (pizzicato). In orchestral repertoire and tango music, both arco and pizzicato are employed. In jazz, pizzicato is the norm, except for some solos and also occasional written parts in modern jazz that call for bowing. In most other genres, such as blues and rockabilly, the bass is plucked.	 The double bass is a transposing instrument and sounds one octave lower than notated.')

','Philippe Clay, born Philippe Mathevet, (March 7, 1927 – December 13, 2007) was a French mime artist, singer and actor.	 He was known for his tall and slim silhouette (he was 1,90 m tall) and for his interpretations of songs by Charles Aznavour, Claude Nougaro, Jean-Roger Caussimon, Boris Vian, Serge Gainsbourg, Jean Yanne, Léo Ferré, Jacques Datin, Jean-Claude Massoulier or Bernard Dimey. He interpretated “ La Complainte des Apaches ” for the TV series Les Brigades du Tigre, written by Henri Djian and composed by Claude Bolling. The music may be performed by a single musician, sometimes then called a recital, or by a musical ensemble, such as an orchestra, a choir, or a musical band. Informal names for a concert include &quot;show&quot; and &quot;gig&quot;. Concerts are held in a wide variety of settings or venues, including pubs, nightclubs, houses, barns, dedicated concert halls, entertainment centres, large multipurpose buildings, and even sports stadiums. A concert held in a very large venue is sometimes called an arena concert.','A concert is a live performance, usually of music, before an audience. The music may be performed by a single musician, sometimes then called a recital, or by a musical ensemble, such as an orchestra, a choir, or a musical band. Informal names for a concert include &quot;show&quot; and &quot;gig&quot;. Concerts are held in a wide variety of settings or venues, including pubs, nightclubs, houses, barns, dedicated concert halls, entertainment centres, large multipurpose buildings, and even sports stadiums. A concert held in a very large venue is sometimes called an arena concert. Regardless of the venue, musicians usually perform on a stage. Before the dominance of recorded music, concerts would be the only opportunity one would generally have to hear musicians play.	 	 While the principal reason for a concert is the opportunity for the musicians to perform in front of an audience, even the most purely artistic of endeavors will see gains. Concerts provide the musicians exposure to the public. An attendee will probably see the musicians perform again if the concert was worthwhile. Recording artists usually go on tours to promote record sales and introduce their fans to new musical compositions. Some musicians and musical groups are known for consistently touring and holding concerts, others rarely so.	 	 The duration of concerts vary significantly. For major concerts, it could generally take more than 6 hours, including support bands.')
